    ('rag-l2-naive-limitations', 'RAG Basics', 'intermediate', 'rag_lesson_2', 'What is a major limitation of Naive RAG?', 'It struggles with low precision (irrelevant chunks) and lost context (poor chunk boundaries)', ['It requires running backpropagation on GPUs', 'It can only process text containing numbers', 'It does not support English tokenization'], 'Naive RAG fetches chunks solely by raw vector similarity, often leading to missing surrounding context or bringing in noisy, irrelevant pages.'),
    ('rag-l2-query-translation', 'RAG Basics', 'advanced', 'rag_lesson_2', 'What is Query Translation (or Query Expansion) in advanced RAG?', "Rewriting or generating multiple variations of the user's query to capture a wider range of relevant chunks", ['Translating the English user prompt into Russian using translate_all', 'Converting database records to CSV files', 'Encrypting the query vector using AES'], 'Query translation modifies the input query (e.g. generating sub-questions) to fetch richer, more comprehensive context from the database.'),
    ('rag-l2-routing', 'RAG Basics', 'advanced', 'rag_lesson_2', "What does a 'Router' do in an advanced RAG architecture?", "It decides which database or search tool is best suited to answer the user's query", ['It connects the bot to the local internet router hardware', 'It splits the text chunks into sentences using regex', 'It resets the session statistics of the user'], 'Routing directs queries to the appropriate vector store or API (e.g., routing code queries to GitHub and medical queries to a medical DB).'),
    ('rag-l2-reranking', 'RAG Basics', 'advanced', 'rag_lesson_2', "What is the purpose of a 'Reranker' in advanced RAG?", 'To re-evaluate retrieved chunks using a cross-encoder model to sort them by actual relevance before prompt insertion', ['To change the primary keys of the SQLite database tables', 'To update the vocabulary indexes of the tokenizer', 'To sort the user leaderboard statistics'], 'Vector databases are fast but can rank chunks poorly. A reranker processes the top candidates more deeply, sorting the best context to the top.'),
    ('rag-l2-cross-encoder-vs-bi', 'RAG Basics', 'advanced', 'rag_lesson_2', 'Why are cross-encoders used for reranking while bi-encoders (embeddings) are used for retrieval?', 'Bi-encoders encode text separately for fast search, while cross-encoders process the query and document together for high accuracy', ['Bi-encoders only run on CPU; cross-encoders run on GPU', 'Cross-encoders do not support vector databases', 'Bi-encoders are non-differentiable'], 'Bi-encoders enable fast similarity indexing. Cross-encoders are slower but capture deep interactions between query and document text.'),
    ('rag-l2-parent-child-chunking', 'RAG Basics', 'advanced', 'rag_lesson_2', 'What is Parent-Child (or Sentence-Window) chunking?', 'Retrieving small sentence chunks for precise matching, but feeding their larger parent document context to the LLM', ['Splitting the database into parent tables and child tables', 'Using recursive loops during backpropagation', 'Updating weights and biases in opposite directions'], 'Sentence chunks match queries easily, but lack surrounding context. Parent-child retrieval keeps matches small while providing full context to the LLM.'),
    ('rag-l2-recursive-splitting', 'RAG Basics', 'intermediate', 'rag_lesson_2', 'What is recursive character splitting in document preprocessing?', 'Splitting text using a list of separators (like paragraphs, sentences, and words) iteratively to keep chunks close to a target size', ['A method for encrypting character strings recursively', 'Saving document lines in reverse order in SQLite', 'Running matrix multiplications in a loop'], 'Recursive splitting ensures chunk boundaries fall on natural text pauses (like double newlines or periods) rather than cutting words in half.'),
    ('rag-l2-sliding-window', 'RAG Basics', 'intermediate', 'rag_lesson_2', 'What is a sliding window chunking strategy?', 'Creating chunks that overlap with adjacent chunks by a set number of characters or tokens', ['Scrolling through the active SQLite database tables', 'A technique for displaying video overlays in Telegram', 'Modifying the learning rate over time'], "Overlapping chunks ensure that information located right at the edge of a chunk boundary isn't lost or split across contexts."),
    ('rag-l2-lost-in-the-middle', 'RAG Basics', 'advanced', 'rag_lesson_2', "What is the 'lost in the middle' phenomenon in LLMs?", 'LLMs attend strongly to the beginning and end of long contexts, often overlooking information placed in the middle', ['Gradients vanishing in the hidden layers during training', 'User queries getting lost due to database timeout errors', 'Tokens falling outside the vocabulary index limit'], 'Research shows LLMs fail to retrieve facts stuffed in the middle of long prompts, highlighting the need to limit context to highly relevant chunks.'),
    ('rag-l2-dense-vs-sparse', 'RAG Basics', 'advanced', 'rag_lesson_2', "In search systems, what does 'dense retrieval' refer to?", 'Semantic search using continuous vector embeddings', ['Traditional keyword matching using BM25 algorithms', 'Joining multiple tables in a relational database', 'Filtering out all non-alphanumeric characters'], 'Dense retrieval matches concepts using dense float vectors. Sparse retrieval matches exact words (like BM25 indexing).'),
    ('rag-l2-bm25-role', 'RAG Basics', 'intermediate', 'rag_lesson_2', 'What is BM25 in information retrieval?', 'A highly popular sparse search algorithm based on term frequency and document length matching', ['A transformer model used for next-token prediction', 'An activation function that replaces ReLU', 'A database backup compression format'], 'BM25 is a standard keyword-based ranking algorithm, often combined with vector search in hybrid setups.'),
    ('rag-l2-reciprocal-rank-fusion', 'RAG Basics', 'advanced', 'rag_lesson_2', 'What is Reciprocal Rank Fusion (RRF) used for in hybrid search?', 'Merging the ranking lists from keyword search and vector search into a single consolidated rank score', ['Multiplying the weight matrices of two attention heads', 'Calculating the average loss over a mini-batch', 'Reversing the order of tokens in the vocabulary'], 'RRF scores candidates based on their rank positions in sparse and dense search results, producing a robust combined list.'),
    ('rag-l2-multiquery-expansion', 'RAG Basics', 'intermediate', 'rag_lesson_2', "If a user inputs 'neural net', why might Multi-Query expansion generate 'deep learning' and 'multilayer perceptron'?", 'To search the database for related terms, ensuring relevant documents using synonyms are not missed', ['To translate the terms into Russian automatically', 'To check for syntax errors in the database schema', "To increase the user's score in the leaderboard"], 'Synonyms and variations help bypass the limitation of embedding vectors which might not align perfectly on rare terms.'),
    ('rag-l2-agentic-rag-concept', 'RAG Basics', 'intermediate', 'rag_lesson_2', 'What is Agentic RAG?', 'An architecture where an LLM agent uses reasoning steps to iteratively search, evaluate, and fetch more data if needed', ['A RAG pipeline that operates only on coding tasks', 'A database seeder that runs without Python scripts', 'A training process that uses reinforcement learning'], 'Agentic RAG gives the model agency to decide when to search, what terms to use, and whether the retrieved context is sufficient.'),
    ('rag-l2-self-rag-evaluation', 'RAG Basics', 'advanced', 'rag_lesson_2', 'What is Self-RAG?', 'A framework where the model generates self-reflection tokens to evaluate retrieval quality and generation correctness', ['A model that fine-tunes itself on its own database', 'A process that deletes incorrect weights dynamically', 'A database index that updates without SQL'], 'Self-RAG integrates criticism steps inside the model output, helping it assess if the retrieved text matches the query and if its answer is correct.'),
    ('rag-l2-metadata-filtering', 'RAG Basics', 'intermediate', 'rag_lesson_2', 'Why is metadata filtering useful in vector databases?', 'It restricts the similarity search to a subset of documents (e.g. only files from year 2026), increasing speed and relevance', ['It automatically deletes all duplicate characters from the prompt', 'It replaces the need for activation functions', 'It runs database compression in the background'], 'Metadata filters (like date or category) narrow down the search space before running vector math, preventing irrelevant matches.'),
    ('rag-l2-hierarchical-node-parsing', 'RAG Basics', 'advanced', 'rag_lesson_2', 'What is hierarchical node parsing in index construction?', 'Organizing document chunks in a tree structure with parent, child, and sibling references', ['Sorting the SQLite database rows by primary key', 'Converting all text characters to uppercase', 'Executing a binary search over weight parameters'], 'A hierarchical index lets the search traverse down from broad document summaries to specific sentence passages dynamically.'),
    ('rag-l2-context-compression', 'RAG Basics', 'advanced', 'rag_lesson_2', 'What is Context Compression (or Summarization) in RAG post-processing?', 'Extracting only the most relevant sentences or summarizing retrieved chunks to minimize prompt token usage', ['Compressing the database file into a zip archive', 'Reducing the dimensions of the embedding vector', 'Lowering the learning rate of the optimizer'], 'Post-retrieval compressors strip out redundant or noisy text from the retrieved chunks, saving context space and API costs.'),
    ('rag-l2-retrieval-evaluation-metrics', 'RAG Basics', 'advanced', 'rag_lesson_2', 'What are two key metrics used to evaluate RAG retrieval quality?', 'Precision (are retrieved chunks relevant?) and Recall (did we find all relevant chunks?)', ['Accuracy and Epochs', 'Logits and Sigmoids', 'Streaks and Leaderboard ranks'], 'Precision measures the lack of noise in retrieved context. Recall measures the completeness of the retrieved information.'),
    ('rag-l3-three-pillars', 'RAG Basics', 'beginner', 'rag_lesson_3', 'What are the three core steps of a RAG pipeline?', 'Retrieve, Augment, Generate', ['Read, Analyze, Group', 'Reorder, Assemble, Grade', 'Randomize, Activate, Gate'], 'RAG operates sequentially: Retrieve matching documents, Augment the prompt, and Generate the final text.'),
    ('rag-l3-embedding-analogy', 'RAG Basics', 'intermediate', 'rag_lesson_3', 'How are embeddings conceptualized in vector space?', 'Coordinates on a map where semantically similar topics are located close to each other', ['A index table inside a relational database', 'A set of binary switches representing transistors', 'A list of strings sorted alphabetically'], "Embedding coordinates map meaning: 'king' and 'queen' will be positioned near each other on this mathematical map."),
    ('rag-l3-finetuning-difference', 'RAG Basics', 'intermediate', 'rag_lesson_3', 'Unlike fine-tuning, why does RAG not suffer from catastrophic forgetting?', "It does not modify the model's weights, leaving its core capabilities unchanged", ['It stores all weights inside a read-only database', 'It runs only on offline CPU clusters', 'It deletes old memories from vocabulary'], 'Fine-tuning alters weights and can cause the model to forget prior skills. RAG simply provides external reading material.'),
    ('rag-l3-ingestion-pipeline', 'RAG Basics', 'beginner', 'rag_lesson_3', 'What is the Ingestion Pipeline in RAG?', 'The offline process of loading, chunking, embedding, and saving documents to a vector store', ['The live chat interaction between the user and the bot', 'The backpropagation pass during model training', 'The process of converting SQLite to CSV format'], 'Ingestion is the setup phase: preparing and indexing reference files so they are ready to be searched during inference.'),
    ('rag-l3-inference-pipeline', 'RAG Basics', 'beginner', 'rag_lesson_3', 'What is the Inference Pipeline in RAG?', 'The online process of retrieving relevant chunks for a user query and generating a response on the fly', ['The database table seeding step', 'The training process that runs on GPU clusters', 'The translation of questions to Russian'], 'Inference is the live run: when a user asks a question, we execute search and generation dynamically to answer it.'),
    ('rag-l3-cosine-similarity-angle', 'RAG Basics', 'advanced', 'rag_lesson_3', 'If two vectors point in the exact same direction, what is their cosine similarity?', '1.0', ['0.0', '-1.0', '90.0'], 'Identical vector directions yield a cosine similarity of 1.0 (cosine of 0 degrees is 1).'),
    ('rag-l3-orthogonal-similarity', 'RAG Basics', 'advanced', 'rag_lesson_3', 'If two vectors are orthogonal (at a 90-degree angle to each other), what is their cosine similarity?', '0.0', ['1.0', '-1.0', '0.5'], 'Orthogonal vectors share no semantic alignment, resulting in a cosine similarity of 0.0 (cosine of 90 degrees is 0).'),
    ('rag-l3-prompt-template-components', 'RAG Basics', 'beginner', 'rag_lesson_3', 'What three pieces of text are typically combined to form the augmented prompt?', "The system instructions, the retrieved context, and the user's question", ['The database schema, the user credentials, and the model weights', 'The activation values, the learning rate, and the loss', 'The vocabulary list, the target labels, and the log files'], "An augmented prompt merges instructions ('Use only the context...'), reference context ('PDF content...'), and user query ('How do I...')."),
    ('rag-l3-grounding-principle', 'RAG Basics', 'intermediate', 'rag_lesson_3', 'What is the grounding principle in prompt design?', "Instructing the model to answer based *only* on the provided context and to say 'I don't know' if the answer isn't there", ['Forcing the database to run on local servers only', 'Removing all activation functions from the transformer blocks', 'Keeping the temperature parameter set to exactly zero'], 'Grounding constraints force the LLM to act as a strict extractor rather than synthesizing outside information, preventing fabrications.'),
    ('rag-l3-document-loaders', 'RAG Basics', 'beginner', 'rag_lesson_3', 'What is the role of a Document Loader in RAG frameworks (like LangChain)?', 'To read text from various file formats (PDFs, websites, markdown) and convert them into raw document structures', ['To upload the model weights to the GPU memory', 'To index database rows in the SQLite cache', 'To format output strings for the user interface'], 'Loaders read the raw source files (from local disks or web APIs) and prepare them for chunking.'),
    ('rag-l3-chunk-overlap-purpose', 'RAG Basics', 'intermediate', 'rag_lesson_3', 'What is the primary reason for adding an overlap size when chunking text?', "To preserve context and ensure semantic meaning isn't lost at the split boundaries", ['To speed up the vector similarity database queries', 'To ensure all weights in the network are non-zero', 'To fit the files inside the SQLite cache limit'], 'Overlapping splits duplicate text at the edges, preventing key sentences from being cut in half and losing their relationship.'),
    ('rag-l3-llm-orchestrator', 'RAG Basics', 'intermediate', 'rag_lesson_3', 'What are LangChain and LlamaIndex referred to as in RAG applications?', 'Orchestration frameworks', ['Vector databases', 'Embedding models', 'Optimization scripts'], 'LangChain and LlamaIndex coordinate the RAG components: connecting loaders, splitters, vector stores, and LLM APIs.'),
    ('rag-l3-embeddings-dimensional-count', 'RAG Basics', 'advanced', 'rag_lesson_3', 'What is a typical vector dimension count for modern text embedding models (e.g. OpenAI text-embedding-3-small)?', '1536 dimensions', ['10 dimensions', '13,002 dimensions', '1 million dimensions'], 'Standard embedding models output dense vectors containing 384, 768, or 1536 floating-point values.'),
    ('rag-l3-nearest-neighbors-search', 'RAG Basics', 'advanced', 'rag_lesson_3', 'What search algorithm is used by vector databases to find similar vectors efficiently without brute force?', 'Approximate Nearest Neighbors (ANN)', ['Linear search over all rows', 'Binary search on sorted integers', 'Regular expression pattern matching'], 'ANN algorithms (like HNSW or IVF-PQ) trade absolute accuracy for extreme speed, making vector lookup highly scalable.'),
    ('rag-l3-knowledge-cutoff-relevance', 'RAG Basics', 'beginner', 'rag_lesson_3', 'If an LLM has a knowledge cutoff of January 2025, how does RAG help it answer questions about a company launch in 2026?', 'RAG retrieves the 2026 launch news from the database and inserts it directly into the prompt', ["RAG fine-tunes the LLM's parameter weights dynamically in real-time", 'RAG bypasses the LLM and answers the question directly using regex', "RAG updates the model's vocabulary file on the hosting server"], 'Since the 2026 facts are fed in-context, the LLM reads them from the prompt and answers correctly, completely bypassing the cutoff limit.'),
    ('rag-l3-hnsw-indexing', 'RAG Basics', 'advanced', 'rag_lesson_3', 'What is HNSW in vector databases?', 'Hierarchical Navigable Small World, a graph-based index for fast vector similarity search', ['A deep learning optimizer that replaces Adam', 'A compression format used for SQLite database files', 'A method for caching token embeddings in RAM'], 'HNSW constructs multi-layered graphs for fast, approximate nearest neighbor search, which is highly popular in vector stores.'),
    ('rag-l3-token-limit-overflow', 'RAG Basics', 'intermediate', 'rag_lesson_3', "What happens if we retrieve too many chunks and exceed the LLM's context window?", 'The API call will return an error or truncate the prompt, causing key information to be lost', ['The database will delete the weights of the model', 'The model will automatically switch to Russian', 'The CPU will overheat due to matrix division'], 'Exceeding prompt limits causes system errors or forces truncation, which is why chunk size and count must be balanced.'),
    ('rag-l3-rag-vs-finetuning-cost', 'RAG Basics', 'beginner', 'rag_lesson_3', 'Which approach is generally cheaper and faster to implement for dynamic document QA?', 'RAG', ['Fine-tuning', 'Pretraining from scratch', 'Reinforcement learning'], 'RAG has zero model training cost and works instantly by updating database files, making it the most cost-effective QA approach.'),
    ('rag-l3-pdf-parsing-challenge', 'RAG Basics', 'intermediate', 'rag_lesson_3', 'Why is parsing PDFs sometimes challenging in RAG pipelines?', 'PDFs are layout-based rather than text-based, making it hard to extract clean, ordered text, tables, and images', ['PDFs cannot be processed by Python virtual environments', 'PDF vectors always have zero similarity scores', 'PDF content is too long for vector databases'], 'Extracting continuous text from two-column PDF papers, headers, footers, and complex tables requires specialized loaders.'),
    ('rag-l3-rag-security-access-control', 'RAG Basics', 'advanced', 'rag_lesson_3', 'How does RAG support document access control (permissions) in search?', 'By filtering retrieval results based on user access permissions before feeding them to the LLM', ['By encrypting the prompt using AES-256 before sending it to the user', 'By resetting the model weights for each user', 'By running all model generation on local databases only'], "Because RAG retrieves chunks from databases, we can apply security filters (e.g. metadata role permissions) to prevent users from seeing data they shouldn't access."),
    ('dl-bp3-core-goal', 'deep learning', 'beginner', 'deep_learning_3', 'What is the primary goal of backpropagation?', 'To calculate how the cost function changes with respect to every weight and bias', ['To generate new images of handwritten digits', 'To increase the learning rate on every epoch', 'To save weights inside a CSV file'], 'Backpropagation computes the gradient of the cost function, telling us how to adjust weights and biases to reduce error.'),
    ('dl-bp3-nudge-types', 'deep learning', 'beginner', 'deep_learning_3', "To change a neuron's activation value, what three parameters can be nudged?", 'Biases, weights of incoming connections, and activations of the previous layer', ['The learning rate, optimizer momentum, and batch size', 'The GPU clock speed, RAM allocation, and CPU cores', 'The output labels, input dimensions, and dataset file path'], "Incoming weights, biases, and previous layer activations are the only mathematical factors determining a neuron's activation."),
    ('dl-bp3-cannot-change-prev-activations', 'deep learning', 'intermediate', 'deep_learning_3', "Why can't backpropagation directly modify the activations of the previous layer?", 'Activations are functions of weights and biases in even earlier layers, which must be recursively adjusted', ['Previous activations are constant values hardcoded in the dataset', 'Changing them would violate the SQLite database schema', 'The GPU memory does not allow writing to prior layers'], 'We can only adjust weights and biases. To change an activation, we must adjust the weights and biases of the layers leading into it.'),
    ('dl-bp3-proportional-influence', 'deep learning', 'intermediate', 'deep_learning_3', "When adjusting weights to change a neuron's activation, why are adjustments proportional to the activations of the previous layer?", 'Neurons with stronger activations have a greater influence on the weighted sum, so changing their weights gives more impact', ['Only neurons with zero activation can be updated', 'It prevents the weights from becoming floating-point numbers', 'It ensures the learning rate remains exactly zero'], 'Because weights multiply prior activations, connections from highly active neurons have a larger effect on the output.'),
    ('dl-bp3-nudge-accumulation', 'deep learning', 'intermediate', 'deep_learning_3', 'How does backpropagation handle conflicting nudges from different output neurons for a single hidden neuron?', 'By summing all desired changes together to find a compromise direction', ['By only executing the nudge from the most active output neuron', 'By ignoring all conflicts and setting the weights to zero', 'By raising an exception and stopping the training session'], 'Different output neurons will demand different changes to a hidden neuron; summing these demands finds the direction that satisfies the group best.'),
    ('dl-bp3-average-grad', 'deep learning', 'beginner', 'deep_learning_3', 'What represents the overall step taken in gradient descent after analyzing all training examples?', 'The average of the gradient vectors computed for each individual training example', ['The maximum gradient value found in the first batch', 'A random step direction to ensure exploration', 'The gradient of the cost function evaluated at zero'], 'To improve performance on the whole dataset, we average the calculated adjustments across all training examples.'),
    ('dl-bp3-mini-batch', 'deep learning', 'intermediate', 'deep_learning_3', 'Why do neural network training pipelines use mini-batches instead of the entire dataset to compute gradients?', 'To speed up training by taking frequent, approximate steps rather than waiting to compute the exact gradient of the whole dataset', ['To fit the entire SQLite database into the GPU cache', 'To keep the learning rate strictly positive', 'To ensure the network remains linear'], 'Mini-batch gradient descent approximates the true gradient using a subset of data, allowing faster convergence.'),
    ('dl-bp3-backprop-vs-numerical', 'deep learning', 'advanced', 'deep_learning_3', 'Why is backpropagation preferred over numerically estimating gradients by perturbing each weight individually?', 'Backpropagation computes the gradient for all parameters in a single backward pass, which is computationally much cheaper', ['Numerical estimation always gets stuck in the global minimum', 'Backpropagation requires no derivatives or calculus', 'Numerical estimation can only run on CPU hardware'], 'Perturbing parameters one by one requires running the network forward thousands of times, which is extremely slow compared to backpropagation.'),
    ('dl-bp3-descent-direction', 'deep learning', 'beginner', 'deep_learning_3', 'In what direction do we nudge the weights vector during gradient descent?', 'Opposite to the direction of the gradient of the cost function', ['In the exact direction of the gradient vector', 'Orthogonal to the gradient vector', 'Toward the nearest coordinate origin'], 'The gradient points uphill; to minimize cost, we must move downhill, which is in the negative gradient direction.'),
    ('dl-bp3-epoch-meaning', 'deep learning', 'beginner', 'deep_learning_3', 'What does one epoch mean in neural network training?', 'One complete pass through the entire training dataset', ['One single step in mini-batch gradient descent', 'The time it takes to compute one neuron activation', 'A database savepoint created after an error'], 'An epoch represents the model seeing every training example exactly once during the optimization process.'),
    ('dl-bp3-stochastic-gd', 'deep learning', 'intermediate', 'deep_learning_3', 'What is Stochastic Gradient Descent (SGD)?', 'Using a single random training example (or a small batch) to estimate the gradient at each step', ['A method that randomizes the weights after every epoch', 'An optimizer that disables all biases in the network', 'A training process that uses no labels'], 'SGD uses random subsets (stochasticity) to calculate fast, approximate gradients, which accelerates optimization.'),
    ('dl-bp3-activation-pattern', 'deep learning', 'advanced', 'deep_learning_3', 'What do the values in the negative gradient vector encode?', 'The relative sensitivity of the cost function to changes in each parameter', ['The exact weights of the input layer neurons', 'The final accuracy rate of the training dataset', 'The coordinates of the local minimum'], 'The gradient components tell us how much the cost changes per unit change in each parameter, showing where edits have the most impact.'),
    ('dl-bp3-mnist-cost-decrease', 'deep learning', 'beginner', 'deep_learning_3', 'What does decreasing the cost function of the MNIST network accomplish?', 'It increases the activation of the correct digit neuron while decreasing all incorrect ones', ['It shrinks the size of the 28x28 pixel grid', 'It deletes all incorrect weights from the database', 'It speeds up the GPU rendering process'], "A lower cost means the output layer's activation pattern matches the desired target vector (1 for correct, 0 for others) more closely."),
    ('dl-bp3-feature-hierarchy-hope', 'deep learning', 'intermediate', 'deep_learning_3', 'Why did we hope hidden layers would form a feature hierarchy?', 'So that early layers could detect simple edges, which later layers combine into shapes and digits', ['To make the model behave as a linear function', 'To avoid computing gradients altogether', 'To store the labels inside the hidden neurons'], 'Feature hierarchies help neural networks generalize by building complex concepts from simpler building blocks.'),
    ('dl-bp3-local-min-quality', 'deep learning', 'intermediate', 'deep_learning_3', 'If a network lands in a local minimum, does it mean it cannot classify digits well?', 'Not necessarily; many local minima yield excellent classification accuracy despite not being the global minimum', ['Yes, it will always perform at random (10% accuracy)', 'Yes, it means the network has forgotten all its weights', 'No, local minima are always identical to the global minimum'], "Hilly cost landscapes contain many local minima that perform well in practice, even if they aren't the mathematical absolute lowest."),
    ('dl-bp3-noise-overconfidence', 'deep learning', 'advanced', 'deep_learning_3', 'Why does the MNIST network confidently classify random noise as a digit?', 'Its training data only contained centered digits, so it never learned to output low confidence for non-digits', ['The network is too small to process noise', 'The sigmoid activation function turns noise into digits', 'The database got contaminated during training'], "Without training examples representing 'none of the above' or uncertainty, the network forces a digit classification on any input."),
    ('dl-bp3-supervised-learning', 'deep learning', 'beginner', 'deep_learning_3', 'What category of machine learning does the MNIST training pipeline belong to?', 'Supervised learning', ['Unsupervised learning', 'Reinforcement learning', 'Self-supervised learning'], 'Supervised learning trains the model on input-output pairs where the correct target labels are explicitly provided.'),
    ('dl-bp3-gradient-zero', 'deep learning', 'intermediate', 'deep_learning_3', 'What happens to the weight adjustments when the gradient of the cost function becomes zero?', 'Adjustments stop, and the weights remain unchanged', ['Weights are reset to random values', 'The learning rate increases exponentially', 'The model switches to binary activations'], 'A zero gradient means we have reached a flat region or local minimum, so gradient descent stops updating parameters.'),
    ('dl-bp3-overfitting-symptom', 'deep learning', 'intermediate', 'deep_learning_3', 'What is a classic sign of overfitting during training?', 'Cost decreases on the training data but increases on unseen test data', ['The model training speed doubles suddenly', 'The gradient vector contains only positive values', 'The SQLite database file size doubles'], 'Overfitting happens when the model memorizes details of the training set instead of learning general patterns, causing test accuracy to drop.'),
    ('dl-bp3-generalization', 'deep learning', 'beginner', 'deep_learning_3', 'What is generalization in machine learning?', "The model's ability to perform correctly on new, unseen data", ['The process of averaging the weights in a layer', 'A method for converting all models to classification', 'The size of the SQLite database table'], 'Generalization is the core objective: we want the model to learn features that work beyond the training set.'),
    ('dl-bp4-core-derivative', 'deep learning', 'advanced', 'deep_learning_4', 'In the backpropagation calculus derivation, what derivative is computed first?', 'The derivative of the cost with respect to the output layer activations', ['The derivative of the weights with respect to the biases', 'The derivative of the cost with respect to the inputs', 'The derivative of the learning rate with respect to epoch'], 'We start at the very end of the network (the cost function) and work backward using the chain rule.'),
    ('dl-bp4-chain-rule-role', 'deep learning', 'advanced', 'deep_learning_4', 'Why is the chain rule from calculus fundamental to backpropagation?', 'It allows us to compute derivatives of composite functions by multiplying partial derivatives back through the layers', ['It forces all weights to remain positive values', 'It replaces the need for matrix multiplication', 'It computes the cost function directly from the inputs'], 'Since activations depend on weighted sums, which depend on prior activations, the chain rule lets us propagate error back step-by-step.'),
    ('dl-bp4-weighted-sum-notation', 'deep learning', 'intermediate', 'deep_learning_4', "In the math notation, what does 'z' usually represent?", 'The weighted sum of inputs plus bias, before applying the activation function', ['The final activation of the neuron', 'The cost of a single training example', 'The learning rate multiplier'], "The activation 'a' is calculated as a = f(z), where z is the weighted sum z = w * a_prev + b."),
    ('dl-bp4-cost-derivative-weight', 'deep learning', 'advanced', 'deep_learning_4', "What is the partial derivative of the weighted sum 'z' with respect to the weight 'w'?", 'The activation of the neuron in the previous layer (a_prev)', ['The bias of the current neuron', 'The derivative of the activation function', 'The value of the cost function'], 'Since z = w * a_prev + b, the derivative with respect to w is simply the activation value a_prev.'),
    ('dl-bp4-cost-derivative-bias', 'deep learning', 'advanced', 'deep_learning_4', "What is the partial derivative of the weighted sum 'z' with respect to the bias 'b'?", '1', ["The weight 'w'", "The previous activation 'a_prev'", '0'], 'Since z = w * a_prev + b, the derivative of z with respect to b is exactly 1.'),
    ('dl-bp4-cost-derivative-prev-activation', 'deep learning', 'advanced', 'deep_learning_4', "What is the partial derivative of the weighted sum 'z' with respect to the previous activation 'a_prev'?", "The weight 'w' connecting the two neurons", ["The bias 'b'", '1', 'The activation derivative'], "Since z = w * a_prev + b, the derivative of z with respect to a_prev is the weight 'w'."),
    ('dl-bp4-three-ratios', 'deep learning', 'advanced', 'deep_learning_4', 'The derivative of the cost with respect to a weight depends on multiplying which three partial derivatives?', 'dC/da, da/dz, and dz/dw', ['dC/dw, dw/db, and db/da', 'dC/dz, dz/da, and da/dw', 'da/dz, dz/db, and db/dw'], 'By the chain rule, dC/dw = (dC/da) * (da/dz) * (dz/dw).'),
    ('dl-bp4-sensitivity-measure', 'deep learning', 'intermediate', 'deep_learning_4', 'What does a partial derivative like dC/dw describe in plain terms?', 'How sensitive the cost function is to tiny changes in that specific weight', ['The final accuracy of the network after training', 'The total number of parameters in the network', 'The speed of the forward pass'], 'A partial derivative measures sensitivity: if we nudge the weight by a small value, how much does the cost change?'),
    ('dl-bp4-matrix-vectorization', 'deep learning', 'advanced', 'deep_learning_4', 'How is the backpropagation step written in vector form for an entire layer?', 'Using matrix-vector operations with the weight matrix transpose and Hadamard (element-wise) product', ['Using a series of SQL SELECT statements', 'By saving each derivative to a text file', 'By executing a linear search over weights'], 'Vectorization represents the chain rule across all layer neurons in a single, fast matrix multiplication step.'),
    ('dl-bp4-vanishing-gradient', 'deep learning', 'advanced', 'deep_learning_4', 'What is the vanishing gradient problem in deep networks?', 'Gradients become extremely small in early layers due to multiplying many small numbers (like sigmoid derivatives), causing learning to stall', ['The weights vector becomes infinitely large', 'The database runs out of space for gradients', 'The cost function reaches absolute zero'], 'Multiplying multiple derivatives that are less than 1 (like the sigmoid derivative, which maxes at 0.25) makes the gradient disappear in deep layers.'),
    ('dl-bp4-relu-benefit', 'deep learning', 'intermediate', 'deep_learning_4', 'Why does the ReLU activation function help with the vanishing gradient problem?', 'Its derivative is 1 for all positive inputs, preventing the gradient from shrinking exponentially in deep layers', ['ReLU is a linear function with no derivative', 'ReLU squishes all activations to exactly 0.5', 'ReLU does not require weights or biases'], 'Since the derivative of ReLU is 1 for positive values, multiplying them back through layers does not diminish the gradient.'),
    ('dl-bp4-average-over-batch', 'deep learning', 'intermediate', 'deep_learning_4', 'In the final gradient calculation, what operation is done to the gradients computed for individual images in a batch?', 'They are averaged together', ['They are multiplied together', 'Only the maximum gradient is kept', 'They are sorted in ascending order'], 'We average the gradients of all batch examples to find a step direction that decreases the cost across the batch.'),
    ('dl-bp4-learning-rate', 'deep learning', 'beginner', 'deep_learning_4', 'What does the learning rate hyperparameter control?', 'The size of the step we take in the direction of the negative gradient', ['The speed at which the GPU processes images', 'The number of epochs in a training session', 'The size of the database index'], 'The learning rate scales the gradient step. Too large causes overshooting; too small makes training extremely slow.'),
    ('dl-bp4-non-differentiable', 'deep learning', 'advanced', 'deep_learning_4', "Why can't we use a step function (which outputs strictly 0 or 1) as the activation function in gradient descent?", 'Its derivative is 0 everywhere (and undefined at 0), meaning there is no gradient direction to slide down', ['It consumes too much GPU memory', 'It requires too many biases', 'It cannot be saved in a database'], 'Gradient descent relies on continuous derivatives. Step functions have flat slopes, giving no clues about which direction is downhill.'),
    ('dl-bp4-cost-landscape', 'deep learning', 'intermediate', 'deep_learning_4', 'What is a cost landscape?', 'The multi-dimensional surface representing cost values for every combination of weights and biases', ['The hardware layout of the GPU clusters', 'The dataset structure of the input images', 'The directory containing the project code'], 'The cost landscape is the mathematical terrain we navigate during training, searching for valleys (minima).'),
    ('dl-bp4-local-min-valley-why', 'deep learning', 'beginner', 'deep_learning_4', 'What does reaching a local minimum represent in the cost landscape?', 'A valley where any small step in any direction increases the cost', ['A peak where the cost is maximized', 'A flat plain where the slope is infinite', 'A system crash due to lack of RAM'], 'A local minimum is a stable point where the cost is lower than its immediate surroundings, causing gradient descent to settle.'),
    ('dl-gd-overshooting', 'deep learning', 'intermediate', 'deep_learning_4', 'What happens if the learning rate is too large?', 'The optimizer will overshoot the minimum and potentially diverge, causing the cost to increase', ['The model will train too slowly', 'The weights will be set to zero', 'The database will fail to commit changes'], 'A large step can jump right over the valley and land higher up on the opposite side, destabilizing training.'),
    ('dl-bp4-backpropagation-layers', 'deep learning', 'beginner', 'deep_learning_4', 'In what order are the derivatives calculated during backpropagation?', 'From the output layer backward to the input layer', ['From the input layer forward to the output layer', 'In a random order to ensure exploration', 'All layers are calculated simultaneously in parallel'], 'Error flows backward, which is why it is called backpropagation (backward propagation of errors).'),
    ('dl-bp4-derivative-notation', 'deep learning', 'intermediate', 'deep_learning_4', "What does the term 'da/dz' represent in the chain rule chain?", 'The derivative of the activation function evaluated at the weighted sum z', ['The change in weights per unit change in biases', 'The final output prediction of the model', 'The database index of that layer'], "Since a = f(z), da/dz is the derivative of the activation function f'(z)."),
    ('dl-bp4-multi-layer-compaction', 'deep learning', 'advanced', 'deep_learning_4', 'Why does adding layers make backpropagation calculus deeper?', 'Each new layer adds another composite function, requiring more terms in the chain rule product', ['It requires resetting all prior weights to zero', 'It makes the model linear', 'It removes the need for biases'], 'More layers mean more composite function wrappers, extending the chain of partial derivatives back to the input.'),
    ('dl-tr5-attention-core', 'deep learning', 'beginner', 'deep_learning_5', 'What is the main purpose of the attention mechanism in transformers?', 'To allow the model to focus on specific related tokens when processing a word, built dynamically based on context', ['To force the user to pay attention to the screen', 'To index database tables using primary keys', 'To speed up video rendering in Telegram'], 'Attention dynamically routes information between tokens, updating their representations based on nearby words.'),
    ('dl-tr5-embeddings', 'deep learning', 'intermediate', 'deep_learning_5', 'What is a word embedding?', 'A high-dimensional vector representation of a word that encodes its semantic meaning', ['A database row containing the word string', 'A translation of the word into binary code', 'The character count of the word'], 'Embeddings map words into a continuous vector space where semantically similar words are located close to each other.'),
    ('dl-tr5-contextual-representation', 'deep learning', 'intermediate', 'deep_learning_5', 'Why do transformers need attention to update word embeddings?', "Words change meaning based on context (e.g., 'river bank' vs. 'money bank'), so embeddings must adapt to surrounding words", ['Word embeddings are otherwise kept constant and can never change', 'To verify that the word is spelled correctly', 'To write the outputs directly to a SQLite database'], 'Static embeddings cannot capture polysemy (multiple meanings); attention builds context-aware representations.'),
    ('dl-tr5-positional-encoding', 'deep learning', 'intermediate', 'deep_learning_5', 'Why do transformers use positional encodings?', 'To feed word order information to the model, since the attention mechanism itself is order-independent', ['To index database records in chronological order', 'To select the highest activation value in the final layer', 'To reduce the file size of the model weights'], 'Attention processes all words simultaneously. Positional encodings add positional vectors so the model knows the order of words.'),
    ('dl-tr5-self-attention-direction', 'deep learning', 'advanced', 'deep_learning_5', 'What does self-attention compute for a sequence of tokens?', 'A set of attention weights showing how much each token should attend to every other token in the sequence', ['The average spelling similarity between tokens', 'The total number of tokens in the vocabulary', 'The database join parameters'], 'Self-attention calculates pairwise relationships, allowing tokens to update their state based on their neighbors.'),
    ('dl-tr5-transformer-input', 'deep learning', 'beginner', 'deep_learning_5', 'What is the input to a transformer block?', 'A sequence of vectors representing token embeddings plus positional encodings', ['A single text string with no formatting', 'A list of SQL queries for the database', 'The weights of the output layer'], 'Transformers process sequences of continuous vectors, representing text that has been tokenized and embedded.'),
    ('dl-tr5-residual-connections', 'deep learning', 'advanced', 'deep_learning_5', 'What is the purpose of residual connections in a transformer block?', 'To allow gradients to flow directly through the network during backpropagation, mitigating vanishing gradients', ['To delete unused weights and biases automatically', 'To encrypt user data before sending it to the database', 'To keep the learning rate strictly positive'], 'Residual connections add the input of a layer to its output (x + Sublayer(x)), creating shortcut paths for gradients.'),
    ('dl-tr5-layer-normalization', 'deep learning', 'advanced', 'deep_learning_5', 'Why is layer normalization used inside transformer blocks?', 'To stabilize training by keeping activation distributions scale-invariant across layers', ['To verify that all inputs are positive integers', 'To compress the model weights into binary format', 'To write progress logs to the console'], 'Normalization stabilizes training, preventing activations from growing too large or small as depth increases.'),
    ('dl-tr5-encoder-only', 'deep learning', 'intermediate', 'deep_learning_5', 'What is an encoder-only transformer (like BERT) typically used for?', 'Tasks requiring a deep, bidirectional understanding of the entire input, such as classification or named entity recognition', ['Autoregressive next-token text generation', 'Running databases locally without SQL', 'Generating images from scratch'], 'Encoders look at the entire context bidirectionally, which is great for extraction and classification but not generation.'),
    ('dl-tr5-decoder-only', 'deep learning', 'intermediate', 'deep_learning_5', 'What is a decoder-only transformer (like GPT) typically used for?', 'Generative tasks that predict the next token autoregressively from left to right', ['Named entity recognition and classification only', 'Loading SQLite databases into memory', 'Training word tokenizers without text'], 'Decoders use causal masking to ensure the model only looks at prior tokens, making them perfect for text generation.'),
    ('dl-tr5-causal-masking', 'deep learning', 'advanced', 'deep_learning_5', 'What does causal masking prevent in a decoder-only transformer?', 'It prevents the model from looking at future tokens during training, enforcing left-to-right generation', ['It prevents the database from saving duplicate rows', 'It stops the model from using GPU memory', 'It hides the output labels from the user interface'], 'Masking forces the model to learn to predict the next word based *only* on the words that came before it.'),
    ('dl-tr5-feedforward-sublayer', 'deep learning', 'intermediate', 'deep_learning_5', 'What is the role of the position-wise feedforward network inside a transformer block?', 'To process the representations of each token individually and non-linearly after attention has mixed them', ['To calculate the overall cost of the batch', 'To tokenize the raw text input', 'To save the final parameters to disk'], 'Attention mixes information across tokens; the feedforward sublayer processes each token representation independently.'),
    ('dl-tr5-vocab-size', 'deep learning', 'beginner', 'deep_learning_5', 'What does vocabulary size mean in a transformer model?', 'The total number of unique tokens the model can recognize and generate', ['The number of languages the model has translated', 'The total size of the training text dataset', 'The character length of the longest prompt'], 'Vocabulary size defines the dimension of the final projection layer, representing all subwords, characters, and symbols.'),
    ('dl-tr5-sequence-length', 'deep learning', 'beginner', 'deep_learning_5', 'What is the sequence length (context length) of a transformer?', 'The maximum number of tokens the model can process in a single forward pass', ['The time it takes to train the model', 'The number of hidden layers in the block', 'The database index limit'], "Context length limits the size of the input prompt plus generation, constrained by attention's quadratic memory cost."),
    ('dl-tr5-token-vs-word', 'deep learning', 'beginner', 'deep_learning_5', 'What is the difference between a token and a word?', 'A token can be a whole word, a part of a word (subword), or even a single character', ['Tokens are stored in databases, while words are only in RAM', 'Tokens are always linear, while words are non-linear', 'There is no difference; they are exactly identical'], 'Modern tokenizers split text into subword tokens to handle rare words and keep the vocabulary size manageable.'),
    ('dl-tr5-embedding-dimensions', 'deep learning', 'intermediate', 'deep_learning_5', 'What does the embedding dimension (d_model) represent in a transformer?', 'The size of the vector representation of each token', ['The maximum number of words in the vocabulary', 'The number of layers in the encoder block', 'The database file size in kilobytes'], 'Embedding dimension (e.g. 768 or 12288) is the size of the vectors that flow through the transformer layers.'),
    ('dl-tr5-multi-layer-attention', 'deep learning', 'intermediate', 'deep_learning_5', 'Why do transformers stack multiple transformer blocks (layers)?', 'To build increasingly abstract representations, allowing higher layers to capture long-range dependencies and complex reasoning', ['To reset the gradients to zero in every block', 'To fit the dataset into GPU memory', 'To change the learning rate dynamically'], 'Just like deep convolutional networks, stacking layers allows the model to compose simple features into complex reasoning paths.'),
    ('dl-tr5-cross-attention', 'deep learning', 'advanced', 'deep_learning_5', 'In an encoder-decoder transformer, what does cross-attention do?', 'It allows the decoder layers to attend to the representations generated by the encoder', ['It averages the weights of the encoder and decoder', 'It encrypts the inputs before classification', 'It clears the cache of the vector database'], 'Cross-attention connects the encoder and decoder, which is essential for sequence translation tasks.'),
    ('dl-tr5-attention-head-count', 'deep learning', 'beginner', 'deep_learning_5', 'Why do we split attention into multiple heads?', 'To allow the model to attend to different types of relationships simultaneously in parallel', ['To speed up the network by using multiple CPU cores', 'To keep the weights vector strictly 1-dimensional', 'To write outputs to multiple database rows'], 'Multiple heads allow the model to look at grammatical structure, pronoun references, and factual links all at once.'),
    ('dl-tr5-attention-cost', 'deep learning', 'advanced', 'deep_learning_5', 'Why does standard attention memory scale quadratically with sequence length?', 'Because it computes pairwise attention scores between every token and every other token', ['It stores all weights inside a relational database table', 'It requires training a new reward model for every prompt', 'It resets the KV cache on every single token'], 'Pairwise interactions create an N x N matrix, making memory and compute scale as N^2 with sequence length N.'),
    ('dl-mh6-qkv-meaning', 'deep learning', 'advanced', 'deep_learning_6', 'In the self-attention mechanism, what are the three vectors generated for each token?', 'Query (Q), Key (K), and Value (V)', ['Quality (Q), Kernel (K), and Vector (V)', 'Queue (Q), Keyboard (K), and Variable (V)', 'Question (Q), Knowledge (K), and Validation (V)'], 'Query represents what the token is looking for, Key represents what features the token offers, and Value represents the actual content it shares.'),
    ('dl-mh6-query-role', 'deep learning', 'advanced', 'deep_learning_6', 'What does the Query vector represent in self-attention?', 'A search prompt asking for specific types of related information', ['The target label of the classification task', 'The database query string for SQLite', 'The weights of the output neuron'], "The Query vector is compared with other tokens' Keys to find matching contexts."),
    ('dl-mh6-key-role', 'deep learning', 'advanced', 'deep_learning_6', 'What does the Key vector represent in self-attention?', 'A profile indicating what information this token offers to matching Queries', ['A password used to access the model parameters', 'The primary key of the SQLite questions table', 'The learning rate multiplier'], 'Keys act like indexing tags; when a Query matches a Key, the attention score for those tokens increases.'),
    ('dl-mh6-value-role', 'deep learning', 'advanced', 'deep_learning_6', 'What does the Value vector represent in self-attention?', "The actual semantic content that is mixed into the token's updated representation", ['The floating-point accuracy of the prediction', 'The value of the cost function for that batch', 'The database index coordinate'], 'Once attention weights are calculated, they multiply the Value vectors to construct the updated contextual embedding.'),
    ('dl-mh6-score-calculation', 'deep learning', 'advanced', 'deep_learning_6', 'How is the raw attention score between token A and token B calculated?', "By taking the dot product of Token A's Query and Token B's Key (Q * K^T)", ['By summing the weights and biases of the two tokens', 'By dividing the Query vector by the Key vector', 'By looking up their coordinates in the SQLite database'], 'The dot product measures alignment: similar directions in vector space yield a large dot product, indicating high relevance.'),
    ('dl-mh6-softmax-role', 'deep learning', 'intermediate', 'deep_learning_6', 'Why is the Softmax function applied to attention scores?', 'To convert raw scores into a probability distribution that sums to 1.0', ['To squish values between -1 and 1 using tanh', 'To verify that all weights are positive integers', 'To compress the output layer size'], 'Softmax normalizes scores into attention weights, indicating the exact percentage of attention allocated to each token.'),
    ('dl-mh6-scaling-factor', 'deep learning', 'advanced', 'deep_learning_6', 'Why are raw attention scores divided by the square root of the key dimension (sqrt(d_k))?', 'To prevent dot products from growing extremely large in high dimensions, which would cause softmax gradients to vanish', ['To ensure the learning rate remains positive', 'To fit the attention matrix into GPU memory', 'To round values to the nearest integer'], 'Large dot products push softmax into regions with tiny gradients (saturation); scaling prevents this behavior.'),
    ('dl-mh6-multi-head-definition', 'deep learning', 'intermediate', 'deep_learning_6', 'What is Multi-Head Attention?', 'Running the attention mechanism multiple times in parallel with different linear projections of Q, K, and V', ['Using multiple GPUs to process different batches', 'A group chat of multiple separate AI models', 'An optimizer that updates weights in multiple databases'], 'Multi-head attention projects inputs into smaller subspaces, allowing the model to focus on diverse relations simultaneously.'),
    ('dl-mh6-projection-matrices', 'deep learning', 'advanced', 'deep_learning_6', 'How are Q, K, and V vectors generated from the input embeddings?', 'By multiplying the input vectors by learned projection matrices (W_Q, W_K, W_V)', ['By extracting them from a hardcoded lookup table', 'By taking the derivative of the activation function', 'By using a random number generator on GPU'], 'The projection matrices are parameters learned during training via backpropagation.'),
    ('dl-mh6-attention-output', 'deep learning', 'intermediate', 'deep_learning_6', 'How is the final output of a single attention head calculated?', 'By taking the weighted sum of all Value vectors, scaled by the softmax attention weights', ['By multiplying the Query and Key matrices together directly', 'By averaging all input token embeddings', 'By saving the attention scores to disk'], 'The normalized attention weights act as coefficients to combine the Value vectors of the sequence.'),
    ('dl-mh6-concat-heads', 'deep learning', 'advanced', 'deep_learning_6', 'How are the outputs of multiple attention heads combined before the feedforward layer?', 'They are concatenated together and multiplied by an output projection matrix (W_O)', ['They are averaged and sorted in ascending order', 'They are saved as separate rows in a database', 'Only the head with the highest score is kept'], 'Concatenation merges the outputs of all heads, and the final projection maps it back to the original embedding space dimension.'),
    ('dl-mh6-attention-complexity', 'deep learning', 'intermediate', 'deep_learning_6', 'If sequence length is N, what is the size of the attention weights matrix?', 'N x N', ['1 x N', 'N x 1', 'N x d_model'], 'Every token attends to every token, creating an N x N attention score grid.'),
    ('dl-mh6-attention-complexity-quadratic', 'deep learning', 'advanced', 'deep_learning_6', 'Why is the quadratic scaling of attention a challenge for long context windows?', 'Compute and memory requirements scale with the square of the sequence length, quickly exhausting GPU resources', ['It makes the model non-linear', 'It increases the number of vocabulary tokens', 'It requires resetting the model weights'], 'As N grows, N^2 grows extremely fast, making standard attention expensive for long documents or books.'),
    ('dl-mh6-query-key-match', 'deep learning', 'beginner', 'deep_learning_6', "If a token's Query matches another token's Key closely, what is the result?", 'The attention weight between them is high, causing their Value to strongly influence the output', ['The model throws an error due to duplication', 'The learning rate is cut in half', 'The two tokens are deleted from vocabulary'], 'Close match means high dot product, leading to strong attention allocation and information flow between them.'),
    ('dl-mh6-no-parameters-in-attention', 'deep learning', 'advanced', 'deep_learning_6', 'Does the raw attention computation itself (after projecting Q, K, V) contain any learnable parameters?', 'No, the dot product and softmax operations are purely mathematical operations with no learnable weights', ['Yes, it contains the weights of the hidden layer neurons', 'Yes, it contains the biases of the output layer', 'Yes, it requires training a separate linear classifier'], 'The learnable parameters are in the projection matrices W_Q, W_K, W_V, and W_O, not in the attention scoring step itself.'),
    ('dl-mh6-attention-vs-cnn', 'deep learning', 'intermediate', 'deep_learning_6', 'Unlike Convolutional Neural Networks (CNNs), how does attention process spatial relationships?', 'It is completely non-local; it can connect any two tokens instantly regardless of their distance in the sequence', ['It only processes adjacent pixels or tokens', 'It requires converting all tokens to 2D image grids', 'It cannot run on GPUs in parallel'], 'CNNs have a limited local receptive field, whereas attention allows direct, long-range connections in a single layer.'),
    ('dl-mh6-self-attention-vs-cross', 'deep learning', 'intermediate', 'deep_learning_6', 'What is the difference between self-attention and cross-attention?', 'Self-attention projects Q, K, V from the same sequence; cross-attention projects Q from the decoder and K, V from the encoder', ['Self-attention runs only on CPUs; cross-attention runs only on GPUs', 'Self-attention has no weights; cross-attention has no biases', 'There is no difference; they are identical'], 'Self-attention mixes information within a single sequence; cross-attention links two different sequences (like source and target languages).'),
    ('dl-mh6-attention-visualization', 'deep learning', 'beginner', 'deep_learning_6', 'What does visualizing attention weights help us understand?', 'Which words the model is focusing on to generate or interpret a specific token', ['The exact learning rate multiplier of the optimizer', 'The physical hardware layout of the GPU cluster', 'The database index structure of the SQLite file'], "Attention heatmaps show which token connections are strongest, offering interpretability into the model's reasoning."),
    ('dl-mh6-d_k-definition', 'deep learning', 'advanced', 'deep_learning_6', "In the attention formula, what does 'd_k' represent?", 'The dimension of the Key (and Query) vectors', ['The total number of tokens in the sequence', 'The number of attention heads in the layer', 'The maximum vocabulary size'], 'd_k is the size of the Query and Key vectors (typically d_model divided by the number of heads), used for scaling the dot product.'),
    ('dl-mh6-hadamard-softmax', 'deep learning', 'advanced', 'deep_learning_6', 'What is the output dimension of the Softmax(Q * K^T / sqrt(d_k)) * V operation?', 'N x d_v (Sequence length by Value vector dimension)', ['N x N', 'd_model x d_model', '1 x N'], 'The softmax matrix (N x N) multiplies the Value matrix (N x d_v), yielding a matrix of size N x d_v.'),
    ('dl-gp7-gpt-acronym', 'deep learning', 'beginner', 'deep_learning_7', 'What does the acronym GPT stand for?', 'Generative Pre-trained Transformer', ['General Purpose Translator', 'Gradient Parameter Tracker', 'Global Processing Tokenizer'], 'GPT models are Transformers that are Pre-trained on large text corpora to Generate text.'),
    ('dl-gp7-pretraining-goal', 'deep learning', 'beginner', 'deep_learning_7', 'What is the training objective during the pre-training phase of a GPT?', 'To predict the next token in a sequence of text', ['To classify images into 10 categories', 'To translate Russian text to English bidirectionally', 'To index database tables automatically'], 'Pre-training uses massive unlabelled text data to learn language patterns by playing a game of next-word prediction.'),
    ('dl-gp7-autoregressive', 'deep learning', 'intermediate', 'deep_learning_7', 'What does autoregressive generation mean in a GPT model?', 'The model generates text token-by-token, using previously generated tokens as inputs for the next step', ['The model adjusts its weights automatically without backpropagation', 'The model trains itself on CPU hardware only', 'The model runs database queries in parallel'], "Autoregressive generation feeds the model's output back into its input sequence to generate the next word."),
    ('dl-gp7-temperature', 'deep learning', 'intermediate', 'deep_learning_7', 'What does the temperature parameter control during generation?', 'The randomness of token selection by scaling the logits before softmax', ['The physical temperature of the GPU hardware', 'The learning rate multiplier during backpropagation', 'The database save interval in minutes'], 'Low temperature makes the output predictable and conservative; high temperature increases creativity and randomness.'),
    ('dl-gp7-logits', 'deep learning', 'advanced', 'deep_learning_7', 'What are logits in the output layer of a GPT?', 'The raw, unnormalized scores output by the model for each token in the vocabulary', ['The final probability distribution that sums to 1.0', 'The coordinates of the attention matrices in memory', 'The learning rate decay values'], 'Logits are converted into probabilities using the softmax function before a token is sampled.'),
    ('dl-gp7-top-p-sampling', 'deep learning', 'advanced', 'deep_learning_7', 'What is Top-p (nucleus) sampling?', 'Selecting from the smallest set of tokens whose cumulative probability exceeds the threshold p', ['Selecting only the single token with the highest probability', 'Selecting a random token from the entire vocabulary', 'Filtering out all tokens that contain numbers'], 'Top-p sampling dynamicizes the pool of candidate tokens, preventing the model from selecting highly improbable words.'),
    ('dl-gp7-top-k-sampling', 'deep learning', 'intermediate', 'deep_learning_7', 'What is Top-k sampling?', 'Restricting token selection to the k most probable tokens', ['Restricting the vocabulary size to exactly k tokens', 'Stopping generation after generating k tokens', 'Running the model on k GPUs in parallel'], 'Top-k keeps the candidate pool fixed at a specific size, filtering out the tail of the probability distribution.'),
    ('dl-gp7-kv-cache', 'deep learning', 'advanced', 'deep_learning_7', 'Why do GPT models use a Key-Value (KV) cache during inference?', 'To avoid recomputing Key and Value vectors for past tokens, speeding up generation', ['To store user passwords securely in the SQLite database', 'To bypass the tokenization step entirely', 'To keep the model weights compressed in RAM'], 'Autoregressive decoding is slow because it runs the model repeatedly. Caching prior Keys and Values avoids wasteful recomputation.'),
    ('dl-gp7-unsupervised-pretraining', 'deep learning', 'beginner', 'deep_learning_7', 'Why is pre-training described as self-supervised (or unsupervised)?', 'It does not require manual labels; the training signal is built-in by hiding the next word in the text', ['It requires no training data at all', 'It runs without a cost function or gradients', 'It is trained entirely by human rating buttons'], 'Self-supervised learning uses the structure of the data itself (the next token) as the label, enabling training on billions of web documents.'),
    ('dl-gp7-finetuning-purpose', 'deep learning', 'beginner', 'deep_learning_7', 'What is the purpose of fine-tuning a GPT model after pre-training?', 'To adapt the model to specific tasks, styles, or instruction-following behaviors', ['To reduce the vocabulary size to zero', 'To calculate the total parameter count of the model', 'To delete the SQLite database file'], "Pre-trained models generate text but don't know how to act as helpful assistants; fine-tuning aligns them to follow instructions."),
    ('dl-gp7-tokenization-bpe', 'deep learning', 'advanced', 'deep_learning_7', 'What is Byte-Pair Encoding (BPE) in tokenization?', 'A subword tokenization algorithm that iteratively merges the most frequent pairs of characters or bytes', ['An encryption algorithm used to secure database files', 'A method for multiplying matrices on GPUs', 'A compression algorithm that deletes spaces from text'], 'BPE builds a vocabulary of common subwords, balancing vocabulary size and context length efficiency.'),
    ('dl-gp7-out-of-vocabulary', 'deep learning', 'intermediate', 'deep_learning_7', 'How do subword tokenizers handle spelling mistakes or unseen words without throwing errors?', 'By breaking the word down into smaller, recognized subword tokens or individual characters', ['By replacing the unseen word with a random digit', 'By ignoring the word and deleting it from the prompt', 'By throwing a system exception and stopping inference'], 'Since subword tokenizers include individual characters in their vocabulary, any word can be decomposed and represented.'),
    ('dl-gp7-hallucination-why', 'deep learning', 'intermediate', 'deep_learning_7', 'Why do GPT models hallucinate (generate plausible-sounding but false information)?', 'They are trained to predict the most likely continuation of text based on statistics, not to verify factual truth', ['Their database is corrupted during training', 'They cannot compute the sigmoid activation function', 'The temperature parameter is set to zero'], "GPTs match statistical patterns; they don't have a built-in truth checker or database lookup for facts unless connected to external tools."),
    ('dl-gp7-context-window-limit', 'deep learning', 'beginner', 'deep_learning_7', 'What happens when the input prompt exceeds the context window of a GPT model?', "The oldest tokens are discarded from the model's memory to fit the limit", ['The model crashes due to out-of-memory errors', 'The model deletes its parameters and weights', 'The model switches to Russian translation automatically'], 'Because transformers have a fixed maximum context, prompts exceeding the limit must be truncated, losing historical context.'),
    ('dl-gp7-scaling-laws-gpt', 'deep learning', 'intermediate', 'deep_learning_7', 'What do scaling laws tell us about GPT models?', 'Model performance scales predictably with more parameters, training data, and compute', ['The cost of running the model decreases to zero', 'The model becomes completely linear in its operations', 'The vocabulary size must double every year'], 'Scaling laws help companies estimate how much better a model will be if they train it with more resources.'),
    ('dl-gp7-system-prompt', 'deep learning', 'beginner', 'deep_learning_7', 'What is a system prompt?', 'An initial instruction that sets the behavior, rules, and persona for the AI assistant', ['The command used to start the python bot process', 'A pop-up alert shown to the user on error', 'The database connection string'], 'System prompts act as meta-instructions, shaping how the assistant responds to subsequent user questions.'),
    ('dl-gp7-unembedding-matrix', 'deep learning', 'advanced', 'deep_learning_7', 'What is the unembedding matrix (LM head) in a GPT?', 'The final linear layer that projects token representations back into vocabulary logits', ['The first layer that embeds text into vectors', 'The SQLite database table containing vocabulary', 'The matrix used to calculate attention scores'], 'The LM head takes the output vector of the final transformer block and maps it to a vector of vocabulary size, producing logits.'),
    ('dl-gp7-reinforcement-learning-alignment', 'deep learning', 'intermediate', 'deep_learning_7', 'Why is RLHF used to align GPT models?', "To optimize the model's behavior based on human ratings of helpfulness, safety, and correctness", ['To decrease the model size so it fits on mobile devices', 'To train the initial tokenizer from scratch', 'To speed up the matrix operations on GPUs'], 'Post-training alignment uses reinforcement learning to ensure the model responds in a constructive, safe, and helpful manner.'),
    ('dl-gp7-causal-decoder-gpt', 'deep learning', 'advanced', 'deep_learning_7', "What architectural choice makes a GPT model 'causal'?", 'The use of masked self-attention to ensure tokens cannot attend to future positions', ['The use of biases in the output layer', 'The database connection to the SQLite file', 'The inclusion of image classification layers'], 'Causal attention ensures that when generating the next token, the model only depends on the past, preserving the temporal flow of language.'),
    ('dl-gp7-word-embedding-limit', 'deep learning', 'beginner', 'deep_learning_7', 'Can a word embedding vector change its values dynamically inside a transformer layer?', 'Yes, the self-attention step mixes embeddings of nearby tokens, changing their values to capture context', ['No, word embeddings remain completely fixed from input to output', 'No, word embeddings are only updated during backpropagation', 'Yes, but only if the temperature is set to zero'], 'The input embedding is static, but as it passes through the transformer blocks, attention continually updates the vector to reflect context.'),
    ('dl-bp8-indices-notation', 'deep learning', 'advanced', 'deep_learning_8', "In the detailed backpropagation calculus equations, what do subscripts 'j' and 'k' typically represent?", "Neuron indices in adjacent layers (e.g. neuron 'j' in the current layer and neuron 'k' in the previous layer)", ['The learning rate and epoch counters', 'The database primary key and index coordinate', 'The weight matrix transpose coordinates only'], 'Subscripts map weights to specific source and target neurons, allowing us to keep track of connection paths.'),
    ('dl-bp8-cost-partial-sum', 'deep learning', 'advanced', 'deep_learning_8', 'When computing the derivative of the cost with respect to a previous activation (dC/da_k), why do we sum over all neurons in the current layer?', 'Because a change in the previous activation affects the weighted sums of all receiving neurons in the next layer', ['Because we must average the cost across all training examples', 'To prevent the gradient from becoming zero', 'To calculate the bias term of the input layer'], 'A single neuron in layer L-1 connects to all neurons in layer L. Nudging its activation changes all receiving z-values, so we must sum their influences.'),
    ('dl-bp8-delta-term', 'deep learning', 'advanced', 'deep_learning_8', "In backpropagation formulas, what does the 'error' term delta_j (dC/dz_j) represent?", 'The rate of change of the cost with respect to the weighted sum z_j of neuron j', ['The difference between the predicted label and the correct label', 'The derivative of the learning rate', 'The database row index of the weight'], "Delta (dC/dz_j) is a convenient intermediate variable representing the sensitivity of the cost to a neuron's pre-activation sum."),
    ('dl-bp8-backprop-recurrence', 'deep learning', 'advanced', 'deep_learning_8', 'What is the recurrence relation for the error term delta in layer L-1 based on layer L?', "delta_L-1 = (W_L^T * delta_L) Hadamard f'(z_L-1)", ['delta_L-1 = delta_L * learning_rate', 'delta_L-1 = W_L * delta_L + b_L', 'delta_L-1 = delta_L / W_L^T'], 'The recurrence formula propagates delta backward by multiplying by the transpose of the weight matrix and the activation derivative.'),
    ('dl-bp8-weight-derivative-expression', 'deep learning', 'advanced', 'deep_learning_8', 'What is the final analytical expression for the derivative of the cost with respect to a weight w_jk?', 'dC/dw_jk = a_k * delta_j', ['dC/dw_jk = delta_j / a_k', 'dC/dw_jk = w_jk * delta_j', 'dC/dw_jk = a_k + delta_j'], 'dC/dw_jk = (dC/dz_j) * (dz_j/dw_jk) = delta_j * a_k (activation of prior neuron k times delta of current neuron j).'),
    ('dl-bp8-bias-derivative-expression', 'deep learning', 'advanced', 'deep_learning_8', 'What is the final analytical expression for the derivative of the cost with respect to a bias b_j?', 'dC/db_j = delta_j', ['dC/db_j = delta_j * a_j', 'dC/db_j = b_j * delta_j', 'dC/db_j = 1 / delta_j'], 'Since dz_j/db_j = 1, dC/db_j = (dC/dz_j) * (dz_j/db_j) = delta_j * 1 = delta_j.'),
    ('dl-bp8-chain-rule-expansion', 'deep learning', 'advanced', 'deep_learning_8', 'How is dC/dw_jk expanded using the chain rule for a neural network?', '(dC/da_j) * (da_j/dz_j) * (dz_j/dw_jk)', ['(dC/dz_j) * (dz_j/da_k) * (da_k/dw_jk)', '(da_j/dC) * (dC/dz_j) * (dz_j/dw_jk)', '(dC/dw_jk) * (dw_jk/db_j) * (db_j/da_j)'], 'By tracing dependencies: C depends on a_j, which depends on z_j, which depends on w_jk.'),
    ('dl-bp8-vectorized-gradient-weights', 'deep learning', 'advanced', 'deep_learning_8', 'What is the vectorized expression for the gradient of the cost with respect to the weight matrix W_L?', 'dC/dW_L = delta_L * (a_L-1)^T', ['dC/dW_L = (delta_L)^T * a_L-1', 'dC/dW_L = delta_L * W_L', 'dC/dW_L = delta_L + a_L-1'], 'The gradient is the outer product of the error vector delta_L and the transposed activation vector of the previous layer.'),
    ('dl-bp8-activation-derivative-sigmoid', 'deep learning', 'advanced', 'deep_learning_8', 'What is the derivative of the sigmoid function sigma(x) in terms of its output?', 'sigma(x) * (1 - sigma(x))', ['sigma(x)^2', '1 / (1 + e^-x)', 'sigma(x) * (sigma(x) - 1)'], "The sigmoid derivative is mathematically convenient: f'(x) = f(x) * (1 - f(x)), which is easy to compute once the activation is known."),
    ('dl-bp8-relu-derivative-positive', 'deep learning', 'advanced', 'deep_learning_8', 'What is the derivative of the ReLU function for x > 0?', '1', ['0', 'x', '0.5'], 'For all positive inputs, ReLU has a constant slope of 1, ensuring constant gradient propagation.'),
    ('dl-bp8-hadamard-product', 'deep learning', 'advanced', 'deep_learning_8', 'What is the Hadamard product (denoted by the circle-dot symbol)?', 'Element-wise multiplication of two matrices of the same dimensions', ['Standard matrix multiplication (dot product)', 'The cross product of two 3D vectors', 'A database join operation'], 'Hadamard product multiplies corresponding entries of two matrices: (A * B)_ij = A_ij * B_ij.'),
    ('dl-bp8-backprop-efficiency', 'deep learning', 'advanced', 'deep_learning_8', 'Why does backpropagation cache the activations computed during the forward pass?', 'Because the weight derivatives dC/dw rely on the activation values of the previous layer', ['To display them to the user in the Telegram chat interface', 'To verify that no weights are negative numbers', 'To prevent SQLite write locks during training'], 'Since dC/dw = delta * a_prev, we must remember the activations calculated during the forward pass to compute derivatives in the backward pass.'),
    ('dl-bp8-cost-function-squared-error-derivative', 'deep learning', 'advanced', 'deep_learning_8', 'For a cost function defined as C = (a - y)^2, what is the derivative dC/da?', '2 * (a - y)', ['(a - y)', '2 * (y - a)', '2 * a'], "By basic calculus, the derivative of C = (a - y)^2 with respect to 'a' is 2 * (a - y)."),
    ('dl-bp8-jacobian-matrix', 'deep learning', 'advanced', 'deep_learning_8', "What mathematical structure represents the partial derivatives of a layer's output activations with respect to its inputs?", 'A Jacobian matrix', ['A Hessian matrix', 'A vector of biases', 'A SQLite table schema'], 'The Jacobian matrix contains all first-order partial derivatives of a vector-valued function, mapping inputs to outputs.'),
    ('dl-bp8-hessian-matrix-mention', 'deep learning', 'advanced', 'deep_learning_8', 'What does the Hessian matrix represent?', 'The second-order partial derivatives of the cost function, describing its local curvature', ['The first-order gradients of the weights', 'The activation values of the hidden layers', 'The database log file'], 'The Hessian is a square matrix of second-order partial derivatives, used in advanced optimization algorithms to adjust step directions.'),
    ('dl-bp8-matrix-dimension-check', 'deep learning', 'advanced', 'deep_learning_8', 'If layer L has 10 neurons and layer L-1 has 16, what are the dimensions of the weight matrix W_L?', '10 x 16', ['16 x 10', '10 x 10', '16 x 16'], 'The weight matrix has rows equal to the receiving layer (10) and columns equal to the source layer (16).'),
    ('dl-bp8-bias-vector-dimension', 'deep learning', 'advanced', 'deep_learning_8', 'If layer L has 10 neurons, what is the dimension of the bias vector b_L?', '10 x 1', ['1 x 10', '16 x 1', '1 x 1'], 'Each neuron in the receiving layer has exactly one bias parameter, forming a column vector of size 10.'),
    ('dl-bp8-delta-backprop-relation', 'deep learning', 'advanced', 'deep_learning_8', 'How is delta_L-1 calculated from W_L and delta_L?', 'By multiplying the transpose of W_L by delta_L, then element-wise multiplying by the activation derivative', ['By adding the bias vector b_L to delta_L', 'By dividing delta_L by the weights matrix', 'By using a SQL SELECT statement'], "This is the core backward step: it maps the error back through the weights matrix to the prior layer's pre-activation."),
    ('dl-bp8-batch-size-impact', 'deep learning', 'advanced', 'deep_learning_8', 'How does changing the batch size from 1 to 32 affect the backpropagation memory requirements?', 'It increases memory because we must cache activations for 32 different forward passes simultaneously', ['It decreases memory because we do not need to compute gradients', 'It has no effect on memory since weights are constant', 'It doubles the size of the database on disk'], 'Higher batch sizes process multiple inputs in parallel, requiring the activation cache to store vectors for all 32 samples.'),
    ('dl-bp8-derivative-chain-recap', 'deep learning', 'advanced', 'deep_learning_8', 'In the chain rule product for backpropagation, which term represents the influence of the activation function?', 'da/dz (the derivative of the activation function)', ['dC/da (the change in cost per change in activation)', 'dz/dw (the activation of the previous neuron)', 'dC/db (the derivative of bias)'], "da/dz measures how much the neuron's output changes for a tiny nudge in the weighted sum, acting as a gate for error signals."),
    ('dl-llm9-post-training', 'deep learning', 'beginner', 'deep_learning_9', 'What is post-training in the context of LLMs?', 'The phase after pre-training that includes instruction tuning and alignment (RLHF) to make the model safe and helpful', ['The process of deploying the model to a server', 'The step where the vocabulary size is calculated', 'The phase where the SQLite database is populated'], 'Post-training takes a raw text-completer (pretrained model) and shapes it into an interactive assistant.'),
    ('dl-llm9-pretraining-dataset-size', 'deep learning', 'beginner', 'deep_learning_9', 'What is the typical scale of training datasets for modern foundation LLMs?', 'Trillions of tokens', ['A few thousand words', 'Exactly 10 images', 'Under 1 megabyte'], 'Pretraining requires massive amounts of text—often trillions of tokens—scraped from books, articles, code, and web pages.'),
    ('dl-llm9-post-training-dataset-size', 'deep learning', 'intermediate', 'deep_learning_9', 'How does the size of post-training datasets compare to pretraining datasets?', 'Post-training datasets are much smaller (thousands of examples) but require very high quality and curation', ['Post-training datasets are much larger (quadrillions of tokens)', 'They are exactly the same size', 'Post-training requires no data at all'], 'Alignment requires highly curated, clean dialogs and instructions, which are expensive to write but require fewer samples (e.g. 10k-100k).'),
    ('dl-llm9-rlhf-ppo', 'deep learning', 'advanced', 'deep_learning_9', 'What reinforcement learning algorithm is commonly used in RLHF post-training?', 'Proximal Policy Optimization (PPO)', ['K-nearest neighbors', 'Gradient descent backpropagation only', 'Linear regression'], 'PPO optimizes the LLM policy toward high reward scores while keeping updates stable to avoid catastrophic collapse.'),
    ('dl-llm9-reward-model', 'deep learning', 'intermediate', 'deep_learning_9', 'What is the function of the reward model in RLHF?', 'To evaluate LLM responses and output a scalar score representing human preference', ['To execute coding tools in a sandboxed environment', 'To generate the initial token vocabulary', 'To update the SQLite database table'], 'The reward model is trained on human preference rankings and acts as a stand-in for human evaluators during RL training.'),
    ('dl-llm9-dpo', 'deep learning', 'advanced', 'deep_learning_9', 'What is Direct Preference Optimization (DPO)?', 'An alignment method that optimizes the LLM directly on preference pairs without training a separate reward model', ['A method that randomizes the temperature during generation', 'An algorithm that deletes duplicate parameters', 'A tool for searching databases using vectors'], 'DPO mathematically reformulates the RLHF objective, making optimization simpler, more stable, and less resource-heavy.'),
    ('dl-llm9-system-1-vs-2', 'deep learning', 'intermediate', 'deep_learning_9', "In Andrej Karpathy's analogy, what does LLM token generation represent?", 'System 1 thinking (fast, instinctive, token-by-token output with no active planning)', ['System 2 thinking (slow, logical, self-correcting reasoning)', 'A database query search', 'A random number generation'], 'Generating tokens one by one is System 1 (instinctive/reactive). Wrapping the model in loops and search tools is System 2.'),
    ('dl-llm9-agentic-loop', 'deep learning', 'intermediate', 'deep_learning_9', 'What is an agentic loop (System 2 thinking for AI)?', 'Allowing the model to read its own output, run verification tools, plan steps, and edit its work before delivering a final answer', ['Increasing the learning rate during backpropagation', 'Generating tokens as fast as possible on hardware', 'A database connection loop'], 'Agentic loops build reasoning scaffolds, giving the model time to verify, correct mistakes, and evaluate strategies.'),
    ('dl-llm9-in-context-learning', 'deep learning', 'beginner', 'deep_learning_9', 'What is in-context learning?', "The model's ability to adapt its output based on instructions or examples provided directly in the prompt", ["Updating the model's weights permanently during inference", 'Running a vector search query on the database', 'Compressing the prompt using BPE'], 'In-context learning is temporary and does not alter the model parameters; it relies on the attention mechanism to capture patterns inside the prompt.'),
    ('dl-llm9-finetuning-vs-incontext', 'deep learning', 'intermediate', 'deep_learning_9', 'What is a key difference between fine-tuning and in-context learning?', "Fine-tuning modifies the model's weights permanently; in-context learning only works temporarily within the current prompt", ['Fine-tuning runs on CPU; in-context learning runs only on GPU', 'Fine-tuning has no cost function; in-context learning has no activation function', 'There is no difference; they are identical'], 'Fine-tuning is a training step that updates parameters. In-context learning uses the frozen weights to process prompt examples on the fly.'),
    ('dl-llm9-context-window-attention-cost', 'deep learning', 'advanced', 'deep_learning_9', 'How does context window size impact inference speed?', 'Longer contexts slow down inference because attention compute scales quadratically with sequence length', ['Longer contexts speed up the GPU processing', 'It has no impact since parameters are constant', 'It reduces the vocabulary size'], 'Quadratic scaling means that as the history grows, calculating attention weights for the next token takes progressively longer.'),
    ('dl-llm9-hallucination-mitigation', 'deep learning', 'intermediate', 'deep_learning_9', 'What is a common method to mitigate hallucinations in production AI applications?', 'Retrieval-Augmented Generation (RAG) to provide the model with verified reference documents', ['Setting the temperature to the maximum value', 'Removing all hidden layers from the transformer block', 'Deleting the user settings database table'], 'RAG grounds the LLM in real-world evidence, reducing the need for the model to rely solely on memorized parameters.'),
    ('dl-llm9-scaling-laws-limit', 'deep learning', 'intermediate', 'deep_learning_9', 'What is a limitation of neural scaling laws?', 'They predict average loss decrease, but do not guarantee safety, reasoning breakthroughs, or product reliability', ['They require training only on linear models', 'They cannot be computed using GPUs', 'They decrease the accuracy of the model to zero'], 'Scaling compute and data reduces training loss predictably, but complex downstream tasks like logical reasoning do not improve linearly.'),
    ('dl-llm9-token-limitations', 'deep learning', 'intermediate', 'deep_learning_9', 'Why do LLMs sometimes struggle with simple character-level tasks (like counting letters or reversing words)?', 'Because they see the text as subword tokens rather than individual characters', ['Because they do not have an activation function', 'Because character tasks are not stored in their database', 'Because they only process image inputs'], "Since tokenizers merge letters into tokens (e.g. 'strawberry' is split into 'straw' and 'berry'), the model cannot easily count the internal characters."),
    ('dl-llm9-mixture-of-experts', 'deep learning', 'advanced', 'deep_learning_9', 'What is a Mixture of Experts (MoE) architecture?', 'An architecture that routes each token to a subset of specialized feedforward networks (experts), activating only a fraction of total parameters per token', ['A group chat of multiple independent AI assistants', 'A database that stores weights across multiple servers', 'A model trained by multiple human experts simultaneously'], 'MoE increases model capacity (parameter count) without increasing the compute required per token, by dynamically routing tokens to specific experts.'),
    ('dl-llm9-rlhf-reward-hacking', 'deep learning', 'advanced', 'deep_learning_9', 'What is reward hacking in RLHF?', 'The model finds loops or styles that score highly in the reward model without actually being helpful or correct', ['The model accesses the GPU clock and overrides it', 'The user edits the database weights manually', 'The model deletes the target labels during training'], 'Reward models are approximations. If the policy finds a loophole (e.g. writing very long, polite but empty answers), it exploits it to maximize score.'),
    ('dl-llm9-rlaif', 'deep learning', 'intermediate', 'deep_learning_9', 'What is Reinforcement Learning from AI Feedback (RLAIF)?', 'Using a larger or stronger AI model instead of humans to generate preference ratings for training the reward model', ['Training the model on CPU hardware only', 'A system where models grade their own weights', 'An algorithm that bypasses backpropagation entirely'], 'RLAIF uses AI feedback (often guided by a constitution) to align models, which is faster and more scalable than human rating.'),
    ('dl-llm9-inference-cost', 'deep learning', 'beginner', 'deep_learning_9', 'What is the primary factor driving the operational cost of serving LLMs?', 'The computational and memory cost of processing attention matrices and weights during inference', ['The file size of the Python scripts on disk', 'The cost of sending Telegram API messages', 'The size of the SQLite database file'], 'LLM inference is highly memory-bandwidth bound. Moving parameters in and out of GPU cache for every generated token drives serving costs.'),
    ('dl-llm9-reasoning-tokens', 'deep learning', 'advanced', 'deep_learning_9', 'What are reasoning tokens (or chain-of-thought tokens)?', 'Special tokens generated by the model to think and reason step-by-step before outputting the final answer', ['The primary keys of the SQLite database tables', 'The tokens used to encode the system prompt', "The character counts of the user's message"], 'Chain-of-thought tokens give the model compute steps to reason, plan, and verify details before committing to a final answer.'),
    ('dl-llm9-alignment-tax', 'deep learning', 'advanced', 'deep_learning_9', 'What is the alignment tax in LLM training?', 'The potential drop in raw capability or general knowledge accuracy that can happen when aligning a model to be safe and polite', ['The financial cost of hiring human annotators', 'The database storage tax charged by cloud hosts', 'The speed reduction when running models on GPUs'], "Forcing safety constraints can sometimes restrict the model's output flexibility, leading to slightly worse performance on neutral reasoning benchmarks."),
    ("dl-gd-cost-function-definition", "deep learning", "beginner", "deep_learning_2", "What is the cost function in the context of training a neural network?", "A mathematical function that measures how poorly the network performs by comparing its outputs to target labels", ["A function that calculates the financial cost of running GPUs", "A method that deletes low-priority database rows automatically", "A compression algorithm that shrinks the model parameters"], "The cost function outputs a single value indicating the network's inaccuracy, which the optimization algorithm tries to minimize."),
    ("dl-gd-single-example-cost", "deep learning", "beginner", "deep_learning_2", "How is the cost for a single training example calculated in the 3Blue1Brown MNIST network?", "By summing the squares of the differences between the actual output activations and the desired target values", ["By taking the maximum weight value in the output layer", "By counting the number of active hidden layer neurons", "By average pooling the input image pixels"], "Squaring the differences penalizes large errors heavily, and summing them across all output neurons measures overall discrepancy."),
    ("dl-gd-cost-function-inputs", "deep learning", "beginner", "deep_learning_2", "What are the inputs to the neural network's cost function?", "All the adjustable weights and biases of the network (e.g., 13,000 parameters)", ["Only the raw pixel values of the input image", "The number of hidden layers and epoch counters", "The target labels of the test dataset"], "The cost function evaluates how 'lousy' the current parameter configuration (weights and biases) is over the training set."),
    ("dl-gd-average-cost", "deep learning", "beginner", "deep_learning_2", "Why is the average cost calculated over the entire training dataset rather than just one image?", "To measure and optimize the network's general performance across all variations in the dataset", ["To prevent the GPU from entering an infinite loop", "To ensure all output activations sum to exactly 1.0", "To skip the backpropagation step entirely"], "Optimizing for a single image would cause the network to forget how to classify other digits, so we average cost to generalize."),
    ("dl-gd-calculus-role", "deep learning", "intermediate", "deep_learning_2", "Why can't we find the minimum of a neural network's cost function analytically using basic algebra?", "The function is far too complex with thousands of inputs, making analytical solutions computationally intractable", ["Relational databases do not support calculus operations", "Neural network outputs are non-numeric characters", "The cost function has no local minimum by definition"], "With thousands or millions of parameters, we must use iterative numerical methods like gradient descent rather than solving derivative equations directly."),
    ("dl-gd-iterative-step", "deep learning", "beginner", "deep_learning_2", "In a 1D simplification, if the slope of the cost function is positive at the current input, which direction should we step?", "Shift the input to the left (decrease the input value)", ["Shift the input to the right (increase the input value)", "Keep the input value exactly the same", "Reset the input to a new random value"], "A positive slope means the function increases as the input increases, so we must go left (decrease the input) to find a lower value."),
    ("dl-gd-ball-analogy", "deep learning", "beginner", "deep_learning_2", "What physical analogy is often used to visualize the process of gradient descent?", "A ball rolling down a hilly terrain into a valley", ["A rocket launching into space", "A deck of cards being shuffled", "A magnet attracting iron filings"], "The terrain represents the cost surface, the ball's position represents the weights, and gravity pulls it toward a local minimum."),
    ("dl-gd-local-vs-global", "deep learning", "intermediate", "deep_learning_2", "Does gradient descent guarantee finding the absolute lowest possible value (global minimum) of the cost function?", "No, the algorithm can get stuck in a local minimum (a valley that is not the lowest overall) depending on where it starts", ["Yes, it is mathematically proven to always find the global minimum", "Yes, provided the learning rate is kept completely constant", "No, it can only find saddle points and never a valley"], "Hilly cost landscapes contain many local minima, and standard gradient descent simply slides into the nearest one."),
    ("dl-gd-proportional-steps", "deep learning", "intermediate", "deep_learning_2", "Why is it beneficial to make the step size proportional to the magnitude of the slope?", "It automatically shrinks step sizes as the slope flattens near a minimum, helping prevent the algorithm from overshooting", ["It ensures that the model trains at a perfectly constant speed", "It forces all weights to remain positive integers", "It reduces the number of parameters stored in memory"], "Stepping proportionally to the gradient magnitude allows large jumps in steep regions and precise adjustments in flat valleys."),
    ("dl-gd-gradient-definition", "deep learning", "beginner", "deep_learning_2", "What does the gradient of a function represent?", "The vector that points in the direction of steepest ascent (the direction of fastest increase)", ["The average value of the cost function over time", "The vector that points to the closest coordinate origin", "The ratio of the weights to the biases in a layer"], "The gradient points uphill. The negative gradient points downhill (direction of steepest descent)."),
    ("dl-gd-negative-gradient", "deep learning", "beginner", "deep_learning_2", "What vector gives the direction in parameter space that decreases the cost function most rapidly?", "The negative gradient", ["The positive gradient", "The orthogonal transpose vector", "The vector of all zeros"], "Since the gradient points in the direction of maximum increase, its negative points in the direction of maximum decrease."),
    ("dl-gd-gradient-length", "deep learning", "beginner", "deep_learning_2", "What does the length (magnitude) of the gradient vector indicate?", "How steep the slope is at the current point in parameter space", ["The total number of parameters in the network", "The accuracy percentage of the model", "The physical distance to the global minimum"], "A longer gradient vector means the current hill is steep, while a vector close to zero means we are on a flat surface or near a minimum."),
    ("dl-gd-nudge-importance", "deep learning", "intermediate", "deep_learning_2", "How do the relative magnitudes of different components in the gradient vector help the optimizer?", "They indicate which parameter changes have the greatest impact on decreasing the cost (the most 'bang for your buck')", ["They determine the physical position of the input layer neurons", "They prevent the model from using activation functions", "They automatically round all weights to the nearest integer"], "Parameters with larger gradient components alter the cost function more strongly, indicating where adjustments are most effective."),
    ("dl-gd-smoothness-requirement", "deep learning", "intermediate", "deep_learning_2", "Why must the cost function be smooth and continuous rather than a step function?", "To ensure we can calculate derivatives/gradients to determine which direction is downhill", ["To store the weights inside a flat text file", "To ensure the model runs faster on low-end CPUs", "To limit the outputs to binary 0 and 1 values"], "Discrete step functions have zero slopes everywhere except at step boundaries, providing no directional gradient clues."),
    ("dl-gd-accuracy-vanilla", "deep learning", "beginner", "deep_learning_2", "What is the approximate classification accuracy of the plain vanilla 784-16-16-10 network on new images?", "About 96% (and up to 98% with minor tweaks)", ["Exactly 100%", "Around 50%", "Less than 10%"], "Despite its simplicity, this basic multilayer perceptron achieves 96%-98% accuracy on the MNIST test set."),
    ("dl-gd-random-noise-confident", "deep learning", "beginner", "deep_learning_2", "How does the vanilla network respond when shown an image of random noise?", "It confidently classifies it as a specific digit, showing high activation in one output neuron", ["It evenly activates all 10 output neurons, showing low confidence", "It throws a software exception and stops execution", "It automatically adjusts its weights to learn the noise pattern"], "Because it was only trained on centered digits and forced to make decisions, it has no concept of 'uncertainty' and overgeneralizes to noise."),
    ("dl-gd-hidden-layer-weights-reality", "deep learning", "intermediate", "deep_learning_2", "When visualized, what do the weights of the hidden layer neurons in the trained vanilla network look like?", "They look almost random and noisy, rather than representing clean edges and loops", ["They form perfect horizontal and vertical lines in the center", "They are completely blank with all zeros", "They display the actual digits 0 through 9"], "The network finds a complex local minimum that works mathematically but does not align with human-interpretable edge features."),
    ("dl-gd-backpropagation-mention", "deep learning", "beginner", "deep_learning_2", "What is the name of the algorithm used to calculate the gradient of the cost function efficiently?", "Backpropagation", ["Feedforward propagation", "K-means clustering", "Linear regression"], "Backpropagation uses the calculus chain rule to compute derivatives for all weights and biases starting from the output layer."),
    ("dl-gd-local-minimum-valley", "deep learning", "intermediate", "deep_learning_2", "In the context of gradient descent, what represents a 'valley' in the multi-dimensional cost landscape?", "A local minimum of the cost function", ["A saddle point with infinite slope", "The maximum parameter threshold of a hidden layer", "A state where all weights are equal to biases"], "A valley is a region where all nearby steps go uphill, meaning the cost function cannot be easily decreased further."),
    ("dl-gd-biological-difference", "deep learning", "intermediate", "deep_learning_2", "What is a key difference between artificial neurons in this network and real biological neurons?", "Artificial neurons have continuous activation values, whereas biological neurons fire in binary pulses", ["Biological neurons do not have connections to other cells", "Artificial neurons are faster than the speed of light", "Biological networks do not adjust their connection strengths"], "Continuous activations enable calculus (gradients) to be used for optimization, whereas discrete binary firing is non-differentiable."),
    ("ai-winters", "AI history", "intermediate", "core_ai", "What caused several historic AI winters?", "High expectations met limited compute, data, and brittle methods", ["A ban on linear algebra", "The invention of GPUs", "Models becoming too accurate"], "AI winters followed funding disappointment when systems failed to generalize beyond demos and narrow domains."),
    ("imagenet-impact", "AI history", "beginner", "core_ai", "Why was ImageNet important for modern AI?", "It provided a large benchmark that helped prove deep learning's practical value", ["It invented SQL", "It ended the need for labeled data", "It was only a chatbot dataset"], "ImageNet helped make progress measurable and showed convolutional networks could outperform older vision methods."),
    ("alexnet-significance", "AI history", "intermediate", "core_ai", "What did AlexNet demonstrate in 2012?", "Deep neural networks trained on GPUs could dramatically improve image recognition", ["Symbolic AI had solved natural language", "Tiny rule systems beat all neural models", "Transformers had replaced CNNs"], "AlexNet was a landmark because it combined data, GPUs, deep networks, and engineering into a major benchmark jump."),
    ("scaling-laws", "pretraining", "advanced", "llms", "What do neural scaling laws usually describe?", "Predictable performance trends as model size, data, and compute increase", ["A legal rule for AI copyright", "A guarantee of perfect reasoning", "A method for shrinking every model to zero"], "Scaling laws help teams estimate returns from more parameters, data, and compute, though they do not remove evaluation needs."),
    ("data-quality-pretraining", "pretraining", "intermediate", "llms", "Why does data quality matter during LLM pretraining?", "Bad, duplicated, or toxic data can reduce capability and shape undesirable behavior", ["The model ignores all text quality", "Only the file extension matters", "Quality matters only after deployment"], "Pretraining data is where much of the model's knowledge and behavior originates."),
    ("tokenizer-role", "pretraining", "beginner", "llms", "What does an LLM tokenizer do?", "It converts text into model-readable tokens and back", ["It verifies facts automatically", "It stores user passwords", "It replaces the neural network"], "Tokenizers split text into units the model can process, affecting cost, context length, and handling of languages or code."),
    ("tokenization-surprise", "pretraining", "intermediate", "llms", "Why can tokenization affect model behavior on numbers or rare words?", "The text may split into awkward subword pieces the model has to compose", ["Numbers are never tokenized", "Rare words are always deleted", "Tokenization runs only after the answer"], "Different token splits can make exact spelling, arithmetic, and rare terms harder."),
    ("instruction-tuning", "fine-tuning", "beginner", "llms", "What is instruction tuning?", "Fine-tuning on examples of following user instructions", ["Training only on image pixels", "Compressing a vector database", "Removing all safety data"], "Instruction tuning makes a pretrained model more useful as an assistant by teaching task formats and response behavior."),
    ("lora-purpose", "fine-tuning", "intermediate", "llms", "What is LoRA commonly used for?", "Parameter-efficient fine-tuning by training small adapter matrices", ["Making prompts shorter by magic", "Replacing the tokenizer with SQL", "Guaranteeing no overfitting"], "LoRA adapts large models without updating every original weight, reducing memory and cost."),
    ("overfitting-finetune", "fine-tuning", "intermediate", "llms", "What is a common risk when fine-tuning on a small dataset?", "Overfitting to examples instead of learning robust behavior", ["The model becomes unable to tokenize", "The GPU becomes a vector database", "The model can no longer answer any old task by definition"], "Small or narrow fine-tuning sets can make models memorize style or facts and lose generality."),
    ("rlhf-purpose", "RLHF", "beginner", "llms", "What is the main purpose of RLHF?", "Aligning model outputs with human preferences after pretraining", ["Training the first tokenizer", "Increasing hard drive space", "Replacing all evaluation"], "RLHF uses preference data and reinforcement learning-style optimization to make outputs more helpful and acceptable."),
    ("reward-model", "RLHF", "intermediate", "llms", "What does a reward model do in RLHF?", "It scores outputs according to learned human preferences", ["It executes tools", "It stores embeddings", "It generates the training corpus from nothing"], "A reward model approximates preference judgments so the policy can be optimized toward preferred responses."),
    ("rlhf-limit", "RLHF", "advanced", "llms", "What is a known limitation of RLHF?", "It can optimize for pleasing-looking answers rather than true correctness", ["It prevents all jailbreaks", "It removes the need for system prompts", "It makes models deterministic forever"], "Preference optimization can reward style, confidence, or harmlessness without fully solving factuality or reasoning."),
    ("dpo-vs-rlhf", "RLHF", "advanced", "llms", "Why do teams sometimes use DPO-style training instead of classic RLHF?", "It can optimize preference pairs more directly with a simpler training pipeline", ["It needs no preference data", "It is a vector database", "It only works for image models"], "Direct preference methods can be easier to run than reward-model plus reinforcement-learning loops."),
    ("rag-basic", "RAG", "beginner", "llms", "What is retrieval-augmented generation?", "Retrieving relevant external information and giving it to the model before generation", ["Training a model from scratch on every prompt", "A method for deleting context", "A benchmark for GPU fans"], "RAG improves groundedness by adding retrieved context from documents, databases, or search results."),
    ("rag-not-training", "RAG", "beginner", "llms", "How is RAG different from fine-tuning?", "RAG adds external context at query time; fine-tuning changes model parameters", ["They are exactly identical", "RAG always requires model weight updates", "Fine-tuning only stores PDFs"], "RAG is usually easier to update because documents can change without retraining the model."),
    ("rag-chunking", "RAG", "intermediate", "llms", "Why is document chunking important in RAG?", "Chunks affect whether retrieval returns complete, relevant context", ["Chunks make embeddings unnecessary", "Chunks encrypt the model weights", "Chunk size only affects button colors"], "Poor chunking can split useful evidence or include too much irrelevant text."),
    ("rag-citations", "RAG", "intermediate", "llms", "Why should a RAG app track source citations?", "So users can verify answers and developers can debug retrieval quality", ["To make answers longer automatically", "To avoid storing documents", "To train GPUs"], "Citations support trust and help diagnose whether the model used the right evidence."),
    ("rag-failure-mode", "RAG", "advanced", "llms", "Which is a common RAG failure mode?", "The retriever returns irrelevant context and the generator confidently follows it", ["The database always answers perfectly", "The model stops using tokens", "Embeddings become human-readable prose"], "RAG quality depends heavily on retrieval, ranking, chunking, and prompt integration."),
    ("embedding-definition", "embeddings", "beginner", "llms", "What is an embedding?", "A numeric vector representing semantic or structural meaning", ["A plain-text password", "A Telegram command", "A hand-written grammar rule"], "Embeddings place similar items near each other in vector space for search, clustering, recommendation, and retrieval."),
    ("embedding-similarity", "embeddings", "beginner", "llms", "What does cosine similarity often measure for embeddings?", "How similar the direction of two vectors is", ["How many files are in SQLite", "How expensive a GPU is", "Whether the answer is legally approved"], "Cosine similarity is a common way to compare embedding vectors independent of magnitude."),
    ("embedding-model-choice", "embeddings", "intermediate", "llms", "Why should embedding model choice match the use case?", "Different models capture different languages, domains, lengths, and similarity notions", ["All embedding models are identical", "Only model file size matters", "Embedding models cannot handle text"], "Search quality depends on whether the embedding model represents the relevant relationships well."),
    ("embedding-drift", "embeddings", "advanced", "llms", "Why should you usually re-embed documents when changing embedding models?", "Vector spaces from different models are not directly compatible", ["SQLite requires it by law", "The documents disappear", "It makes LLMs stop hallucinating"], "A vector generated by one embedding model should not be compared to vectors from another model without migration."),
    ("vector-db-purpose", "vector databases", "beginner", "llms", "What is a vector database commonly used for in AI apps?", "Storing embeddings and finding nearest neighbors efficiently", ["Rendering Telegram buttons", "Replacing all application code", "Charging a model battery"], "Vector databases support semantic search over large collections using approximate or exact nearest-neighbor search."),
    ("ann-search", "vector databases", "intermediate", "llms", "Why do vector databases often use approximate nearest neighbor search?", "It makes similarity search fast at large scale with acceptable tradeoffs", ["It guarantees every answer is factual", "It removes indexing", "It only works for tiny lists"], "ANN indexes trade a bit of exactness for speed and scale."),
    ("metadata-filtering", "vector databases", "intermediate", "llms", "Why combine vector search with metadata filters?", "To restrict semantic search to the right tenant, date, product, or document type", ["To make tokens free", "To convert vectors to images", "To prevent all prompt injection"], "Metadata filtering keeps retrieval scoped and relevant, which is critical in real applications."),
    ("agent-definition", "AI agents", "beginner", "agents", "What makes an AI system agentic?", "It can pursue a goal over steps, using context, decisions, and sometimes tools", ["It has a cartoon avatar", "It only answers one fixed FAQ", "It must always run on a robot"], "Agents are defined by goal-directed behavior across actions, not by appearance."),
    ("agent-loop", "AI agents", "intermediate", "agents", "What is a common agent loop?", "Observe, reason or plan, act, then evaluate the result", ["Compile, delete, sleep, forget", "Tokenize once and stop forever", "Train a foundation model from scratch each turn"], "Agent systems repeatedly inspect state, choose actions, and adjust based on results."),
    ("agent-risk", "AI agents", "intermediate", "agents", "Why can agents be riskier than single-turn chatbots?", "They may take actions repeatedly and affect external systems", ["They never use context", "They cannot call tools", "They are always offline"], "Autonomous action raises the impact of mistakes, so permissions, logging, and guardrails matter."),
    ("human-in-loop", "AI agents", "beginner", "agents", "When is human approval especially important for an agent?", "Before irreversible, costly, public, or security-sensitive actions", ["Before reading its own prompt", "For every token it generates", "Only after deployment is over"], "Human-in-the-loop approval is a practical control for high-impact actions."),
    ("tool-use-basic", "tool use", "beginner", "agents", "Why give an LLM tools?", "To let it access capabilities like search, code execution, calendars, or databases", ["To make it conscious", "To avoid all prompts", "To remove the need for permissions"], "Tools extend what a model can do beyond generating text from its internal parameters."),
    ("tool-schema", "tool use", "intermediate", "agents", "Why define clear tool schemas?", "They constrain arguments so tool calls are easier to validate and execute", ["They make hallucinations impossible", "They replace authentication", "They are only decorative"], "Schemas make model-tool interfaces more reliable and easier to parse."),
    ("tool-result-grounding", "tool use", "intermediate", "agents", "After a tool call, what should the model usually do?", "Use the returned result as evidence for the next response or action", ["Ignore it and invent an answer", "Delete the user message", "Retrain itself immediately"], "Tool results are part of the working context and should ground the answer."),
    ("tool-safety", "tool use", "advanced", "agents", "What is a good safety pattern for powerful tools?", "Least privilege plus confirmation for sensitive actions", ["Give every tool admin access", "Hide all logs", "Let prompts override permissions"], "Tooling should expose only needed capabilities and require approval for actions with real consequences."),
    ("eval-heldout", "model evaluation", "beginner", "core_ai", "Why use held-out evaluation data?", "To test generalization on examples not used for training", ["To make the model larger", "To avoid measuring anything", "To teach the tokenizer"], "Held-out data helps detect memorization and estimate performance on new cases."),
    ("eval-human", "model evaluation", "intermediate", "core_ai", "Why are human evaluations still used for LLMs?", "Some qualities like helpfulness, nuance, and instruction following are hard to capture automatically", ["Automatic metrics are illegal", "Humans can inspect model weights by sight", "Benchmarks never change"], "Human judgment remains important where correctness is contextual or subjective."),
    ("eval-regression", "model evaluation", "intermediate", "core_ai", "What is regression testing for AI apps?", "Checking that changes do not break previously working behaviors", ["Training only on regressions in statistics", "Deleting old prompts", "Measuring GPU fan speed"], "AI products need repeatable test sets because model, prompt, data, and tool changes can introduce regressions."),
    ("eval-leakage", "model evaluation", "advanced", "core_ai", "What is benchmark contamination?", "Evaluation examples or close copies appear in training data", ["The benchmark server gets dusty", "The model refuses every prompt", "The tokenizer uses Unicode"], "Contamination can inflate benchmark scores because the model may have seen the answers before."),
    ("benchmark-purpose", "benchmarks", "beginner", "core_ai", "What is the main purpose of an AI benchmark?", "To provide a standardized way to compare performance on a task or capability", ["To certify moral perfection", "To replace product testing", "To store user settings"], "Benchmarks are useful comparison tools, but they do not cover every deployment scenario."),
    ("benchmark-limit", "benchmarks", "intermediate", "core_ai", "Why should benchmark scores be interpreted carefully?", "They may not match your real users, data, tools, or risk tolerance", ["They are always fake", "They measure only electricity", "They cannot be gamed"], "A model can score well on benchmarks while failing important product-specific cases."),
    ("mmlu", "benchmarks", "beginner", "core_ai", "What does MMLU primarily test?", "Broad academic knowledge through multiple-choice questions", ["Speech synthesis naturalness", "Database write speed", "Telegram message delivery"], "MMLU samples many subjects and is often used as a broad knowledge benchmark."),
    ("coding-benchmark-limit", "benchmarks", "advanced", "coding_ai", "Why can coding benchmark results differ from real coding-agent usefulness?", "Real tasks require repo navigation, tests, debugging, and multi-step edits", ["Benchmarks cannot contain code", "Agents never use tools", "All repositories are identical"], "Passing isolated problems is not the same as modifying a living codebase safely."),
    ("context-window", "context windows", "beginner", "llms", "What is a context window?", "The amount of input and generated text the model can consider at once", ["A browser tab title", "A database backup", "A GPU brand"], "The context window limits how much conversation, documents, code, and tool results can be visible to the model."),
    ("context-not-memory", "context windows", "beginner", "llms", "Why is a long context window not the same as permanent memory?", "Context is temporary input; memory requires storing and retrieving information across sessions", ["Long context changes the model weights", "The model remembers every user forever automatically", "Memory means larger buttons"], "A model only uses what is in its current context unless the system adds durable storage."),
    ("lost-in-middle", "context windows", "advanced", "llms", "What does 'lost in the middle' describe?", "Models can pay less attention to information buried in the middle of long contexts", ["The tokenizer crashes on commas", "The model always stops halfway", "The database loses rows"], "Long-context models may still use beginning and end information better than middle evidence."),
    ("context-cost", "context windows", "intermediate", "llms", "Why not always send every document into the context?", "It increases cost, latency, and distraction from relevant evidence", ["Models reject all long prompts", "Tokens are unlimited", "It automatically improves every answer"], "Focused context often beats massive noisy context."),
    ("hallucination-definition", "hallucinations", "beginner", "llms", "What is an LLM hallucination?", "A fluent output that is unsupported, false, or fabricated", ["A model seeing images in dreams", "A required part of tokenization", "A database index"], "Hallucinations are confident-looking generations not grounded in reliable evidence."),
    ("hallucination-cause", "hallucinations", "intermediate", "llms", "Why do LLMs hallucinate?", "They optimize likely text, not guaranteed truth, and may lack grounding", ["They are connected to too many monitors", "They cannot generate grammar", "SQLite forces them to"], "Language modeling can produce plausible text without verifying external reality."),
    ("reduce-hallucination", "hallucinations", "intermediate", "llms", "Which technique can reduce hallucinations in knowledge-heavy apps?", "Retrieve relevant sources and require answers grounded in them", ["Ask for more confident wording", "Remove all citations", "Use only random sampling"], "Grounding with retrieval, tools, citations, and refusal behavior can reduce unsupported claims."),
    ("hallucination-eval", "hallucinations", "advanced", "llms", "How should hallucination rate be evaluated?", "Against task-specific claims and trusted references, not just output fluency", ["By counting adjectives", "By checking if the answer is long", "By measuring keyboard speed"], "Factuality evaluation needs claim checking and reliable references."),
    ("safety-alignment", "safety", "beginner", "core_ai", "What does AI alignment broadly mean?", "Making AI behavior match intended human goals and constraints", ["Making all models the same size", "Centering text on a page", "Encrypting embeddings only"], "Alignment concerns whether systems do what we want, avoid harm, and respect constraints."),
    ("prompt-injection", "safety", "intermediate", "agents", "What is prompt injection?", "Malicious or untrusted text tries to override the system's instructions or tool rules", ["A way to add RAM", "A normal optimizer step", "A vector compression format"], "Prompt injection is especially important in RAG and tool-using agents that read untrusted content."),
    ("jailbreak", "safety", "beginner", "core_ai", "What is a jailbreak in LLM safety?", "A prompt designed to bypass model or system safeguards", ["A database migration", "A GPU cooling method", "A tokenizer merge rule"], "Jailbreaks try to steer the model into disallowed behavior despite safety instructions."),
    ("data-privacy", "safety", "intermediate", "core_ai", "Why is data privacy important in AI applications?", "Prompts, logs, retrieved documents, and outputs may contain sensitive information", ["Models cannot process private text", "Privacy applies only to images", "Tokens erase secrets automatically"], "AI systems often touch sensitive data, so retention, access control, and redaction matter."),
    ("open-source-models", "open-source models", "beginner", "llms", "What is a major benefit of open-weight models?", "They can be inspected, hosted, fine-tuned, and run under more user control", ["They are always free to use commercially", "They always beat closed models", "They need no hardware"], "Open-weight models give teams more control, but licenses, quality, and infrastructure still matter."),
    ("model-license", "open-source models", "intermediate", "llms", "Why should you read an open model's license?", "It may restrict commercial use, redistribution, or acceptable applications", ["Licenses change tokenizer output", "Licenses are only for images", "All open models share one license"], "Open does not always mean unrestricted; license terms can affect deployment."),
    ("distillation", "open-source models", "advanced", "llms", "What is model distillation?", "Training a smaller model to imitate behavior from a stronger teacher model", ["Compressing PDFs into vectors only", "Deleting training data", "Replacing prompts with SQL"], "Distillation transfers behavior or knowledge into a smaller, cheaper model."),
    ("quantization", "local LLMs", "beginner", "llms", "What is quantization used for in local LLMs?", "Reducing weight precision to lower memory and improve local inference feasibility", ["Increasing all weights to infinite precision", "Turning text into images", "Guaranteeing better reasoning"], "Quantization can make models fit on consumer hardware, often with some quality tradeoff."),
    ("local-llm-benefit", "local LLMs", "beginner", "llms", "What is a common reason to run an LLM locally?", "Privacy, offline use, latency control, or cost control", ["To avoid needing any CPU", "To make the model know today's news automatically", "To remove evaluation needs"], "Local inference can be attractive when data control or offline operation matters."),
    ("local-llm-limit", "local LLMs", "intermediate", "llms", "What is a common limitation of local LLMs?", "Hardware limits may reduce model size, speed, or context length", ["They cannot tokenize text", "They require public internet for every token", "They are always more capable than hosted models"], "Consumer hardware can run useful models, but capacity and speed are constrained."),
    ("multimodal-definition", "multimodal models", "beginner", "core_ai", "What is a multimodal model?", "A model that can process or generate more than one modality, such as text and images", ["A model with multiple usernames", "A SQL database with two tables", "A model trained only on plain text"], "Multimodal systems connect text, vision, audio, video, or other data types."),
    ("vision-language", "multimodal models", "intermediate", "core_ai", "What can a vision-language model typically do?", "Reason over images using natural language prompts", ["Only sort database rows", "Only play audio", "Never use text"], "Vision-language models connect visual inputs with language instructions and answers."),
    ("ocr-vs-vlm", "multimodal models", "intermediate", "core_ai", "How is a vision-language model different from plain OCR?", "It can reason about visual content beyond just extracting text", ["It cannot read text", "It only stores vectors", "It is always smaller than OCR"], "OCR extracts text; VLMs may interpret charts, layout, objects, and relationships."),
    ("coding-agent-definition", "coding agents", "beginner", "coding_ai", "What is a coding agent?", "An AI assistant that can inspect, modify, run, and reason about codebases", ["A model that only writes poems", "A compiler flag", "A database migration"], "Coding agents combine language understanding with tools for files, tests, terminals, and version control."),
    ("coding-agent-tests", "coding agents", "beginner", "coding_ai", "Why should coding agents run tests when possible?", "Tests provide feedback that edits still work as intended", ["Tests make code private", "Tests replace reading code", "Tests guarantee perfect UX"], "Tests are an important signal, though they do not prove every behavior is correct."),
    ("coding-agent-diff", "coding agents", "intermediate", "coding_ai", "Why should a coding agent review its own diff?", "To catch unintended file changes, secrets, or scope creep before finishing", ["Diffs are only for images", "Reviewing diffs deletes bugs automatically", "It replaces all tests"], "Diff review helps keep changes focused and auditable."),
    ("repo-context", "coding agents", "intermediate", "coding_ai", "Why is repository context important for coding agents?", "Existing patterns and APIs determine the safest implementation style", ["All repos use identical architecture", "Context is only needed for comments", "It makes syntax optional"], "Good coding agents adapt to the codebase rather than inventing incompatible patterns."),
    ("swe-bench", "coding agents", "advanced", "coding_ai", "What does SWE-bench-style evaluation aim to test?", "Whether agents can fix real software issues in repositories", ["Whether a chatbot can sing", "Whether embeddings are encrypted", "Whether GPUs are quiet"], "Repository-level tasks test code navigation, patching, and validation more realistically than isolated puzzles."),
    ("temperature", "model evaluation", "beginner", "llms", "What does the temperature setting usually control?", "Randomness in token sampling", ["The physical GPU temperature only", "The number of database rows", "The model's license"], "Higher temperature generally increases variety; lower temperature makes outputs more deterministic."),
    ("top-p", "model evaluation", "intermediate", "llms", "What does top-p sampling do?", "Samples from the smallest token set whose cumulative probability reaches p", ["Always picks the longest word", "Deletes low-quality datasets", "Trains preference models"], "Top-p controls diversity by limiting sampling to a probability mass rather than a fixed count."),
    ("beam-search", "model evaluation", "advanced", "llms", "Why is beam search less common for open-ended assistant responses?", "It can produce generic high-probability text and reduce diversity", ["It cannot generate text", "It requires a vector database", "It only works for images"], "Beam search is useful in some structured generation tasks but not always ideal for conversational quality."),
    ("system-prompt", "tool use", "beginner", "agents", "What is a system prompt commonly used for?", "Setting high-priority behavior, constraints, and role instructions", ["Storing model weights", "Encrypting vectors", "Measuring benchmark leakage"], "System prompts guide behavior and usually have higher priority than user messages."),
    ("structured-output", "tool use", "intermediate", "agents", "Why ask an LLM for structured output such as JSON?", "It makes downstream parsing and validation easier", ["It improves every answer's truth automatically", "It removes the need for schemas", "It makes text unreadable to the model"], "Structured output is useful when software must consume the model's response."),
    ("function-calling", "tool use", "intermediate", "agents", "What problem does function calling help solve?", "Mapping model intent to validated tool invocations", ["Making all tools public", "Replacing the event loop", "Avoiding authentication"], "Function calling gives the model a controlled interface for external actions."),
    ("agent-memory", "AI agents", "advanced", "agents", "What should durable agent memory store?", "Useful stable facts or decisions, not every raw token forever", ["All secrets by default", "Only random thoughts", "Nothing after user consent"], "Memory should be selective, scoped, and privacy-aware."),
    ("planning-limit", "AI agents", "advanced", "agents", "What is a risk of long autonomous planning?", "The agent may compound early mistakes over many steps", ["It eliminates tool errors", "It makes permissions unnecessary", "It prevents all hallucinations"], "Long loops need checkpoints, evaluation, and sometimes human approval."),
    ("reranking", "RAG", "advanced", "llms", "What is a reranker used for in RAG?", "Reordering retrieved candidates by relevance before generation", ["Training the base model from scratch", "Changing Telegram settings", "Compressing GPU memory"], "Rerankers can improve the quality of final context by scoring candidate passages more carefully."),
    ("hybrid-search", "RAG", "intermediate", "llms", "What is hybrid search in RAG?", "Combining keyword search with vector search", ["Using two Telegram bots", "Mixing Python and SQL syntax randomly", "Deleting metadata filters"], "Hybrid search often improves recall by capturing exact terms and semantic similarity."),
    ("embedding-dimensions", "embeddings", "intermediate", "llms", "What does embedding dimensionality affect?", "Storage, search cost, and representational capacity", ["Telegram command names", "Whether a model can use tools", "The user's streak"], "Larger vectors can represent more nuance but cost more to store and search."),
    ("vector-index-rebuild", "vector databases", "advanced", "llms", "When might a vector index need rebuilding?", "After changing embedding models, distance metrics, or index parameters", ["Every time a user clicks a button", "Only when the model says hello", "Never under any circumstances"], "Index settings and embedding spaces define how search behaves, so major changes may require rebuilding."),
    ("safety-evals", "safety", "advanced", "core_ai", "What are safety evaluations intended to find?", "Harmful capabilities, policy failures, jailbreak susceptibility, or risky behavior", ["Only benchmark speed", "Only GPU cost", "Only UI colors"], "Safety evals probe behavior under adversarial, sensitive, or policy-relevant conditions."),
    ("red-teaming", "safety", "intermediate", "core_ai", "What is red-teaming an AI system?", "Actively probing for failures, misuse paths, and unsafe behavior", ["Painting the UI red", "Compressing model weights", "Sorting embeddings alphabetically"], "Red-teaming helps find issues before real users or attackers do."),
    ("calibration", "model evaluation", "advanced", "core_ai", "What does model calibration refer to?", "Whether confidence estimates match actual correctness rates", ["Centering text on screen", "Making all outputs short", "Encrypting benchmark data"], "A calibrated model's stated confidence should correspond to how often it is right."),
    ("latency-throughput", "model evaluation", "intermediate", "core_ai", "Why measure latency and throughput for AI products?", "User experience and cost depend on how fast and how many requests the system can serve", ["Only accuracy matters", "Latency is never visible", "Throughput replaces safety"], "Production evaluation includes quality plus operational metrics."),
    ("batching-inference", "local LLMs", "advanced", "llms", "Why batch requests during inference?", "To improve hardware utilization and throughput", ["To make outputs private by default", "To reduce all prompts to one token", "To skip tokenization"], "Batching can make accelerators more efficient, though it may affect latency."),
    ("kv-cache", "transformers", "advanced", "llms", "What is the KV cache used for during LLM generation?", "Reusing previous attention keys and values to speed up next-token generation", ["Saving user passwords", "Training embeddings", "Replacing all context"], "The KV cache avoids recomputing attention state for prior tokens during autoregressive decoding."),
    ("attention-complexity", "attention", "advanced", "llms", "Why is standard attention expensive for very long contexts?", "Its pairwise token interactions scale roughly quadratically with sequence length", ["It uses no matrix operations", "It stores only one token", "It cannot run on GPUs"], "Every token attending to many other tokens becomes costly as context grows."),
    ("encoder-decoder", "transformers", "intermediate", "llms", "What is an encoder-decoder transformer often used for?", "Tasks that transform an input sequence into an output sequence, such as translation", ["Only storing embeddings", "Only running Telegram bots", "Only replacing SQLite"], "Encoder-decoder designs are common when the model consumes an input and generates a separate output."),
    ("decoder-only", "transformers", "intermediate", "llms", "Why are many chat LLMs decoder-only transformers?", "They are well suited to autoregressive next-token generation", ["They cannot generate text", "They require no pretraining", "They only classify images"], "Decoder-only models generate continuations token by token, which fits chat and completion tasks."),
    ("moe-models", "transformers", "advanced", "llms", "What is a mixture-of-experts model?", "A model that routes tokens through selected expert subnetworks", ["A group chat of human experts", "A vector database table", "A tokenizer with no vocabulary"], "MoE can increase parameter count while activating only part of the network per token."),
    ("catastrophic-forgetting", "fine-tuning", "advanced", "llms", "What is catastrophic forgetting in fine-tuning?", "Losing previously useful capabilities while optimizing on new data", ["Forgetting the API token", "Deleting the SQLite file", "A vector index crash"], "Fine-tuning can over-specialize the model and degrade broad abilities."),
